\ie
\c 1
\s1 David learns about Sha’ul’s death
\s4 Full kingdom
\p
\v 1 \add After\add* David returned from \add slaughtering\add* the Amalekites, he stayed in Tsiklag for two days. (\add King\add* Sha’ul \add was dead by this time\add*.)
\v 2 Then on the third day, wow, a man came from Sha’ul’s camp. He had torn clothes and dirt on his head, and when he got to David he \add fell onto his knees and bowed low\add*.
\v 3 “Where \add have you come from\add*?” David \add asked\add* him.
\p “I \add was in Yisrael’s camp, but managed to escape\add*.” he \add replied\add*.
\v 4 “\add Why? What happened?\add*” David \add demanded\add*. “Tell me, please,”
\p “\add Our\add* people fled from the battle,” the man said. “Many fell and died. Even Sha’ul and his son Yonatan died.”
\p
\v 5 “How do you know that Sha’ul and Yonatan died?” David \add asked\add* the young man who’d \add brought the news\add*.
\p
\v 6 “I happened to be on Mt. Gilboa,” the young man \add replied\add*, “and listen, Sha’ul was leaning on his spear. Then wow, the chariots and the masters of the chariot horses overtook him,\x + \xo 1:6-10: \xt 1Sam 31:1-6; 1Ch 10:1-6.\x*
\v 7 and he turned around and saw me. He called me and I \add answered\add*, ‘Here I am.’
\v 8 ‘Who are you?’ he \add asked\add*. ‘I’m an Amalekite,’ I told him.
\v 9 Then he said to me, ‘Please, \add come over here\add* and kill me, because \add although I’m still alive, the pain is unbearable\add*.’
\v 10 \add So\add* I stood over him and killed him, because I knew that \add with those wounds\add*, he wouldn’t live. Then I took the crown off his head and the bracelet on his arm, and I brought them here to you, my master.”
\p
\v 11 Then David pulled at his clothes \add with his hands\add* and tore them, and all the men with him \add did the same\add*,
\v 12 and they mourned and wept and fasted until the evening for Sha’ul and for his son Yonatan, and for Yahweh’s people, because \add many\add* \add Israelis had been killed\add*.
\p
\v 13 Then David \add asked\add* the young man \add who’d brought the news\add*, “Where are you from?”
\p “I’m a foreigner’s son,” he \add replied\add*, “an Amalekite.”
\v 14 “How come you weren’t afraid to \add kill\add* Yahweh’s anointed \add king\add* \add with your own hands\add*?” David \add asked\add* him.
\v 15 Then David called to one of \add his\add* young men, “Come \add over here\add* \add and\add* \add execute\add* him.” \add So\add* he struck him, and he died.
\v 16 “Your blood’s on your \add own\add* head,” David told \add the Amalekite\add*, “because \add you admitted in your own words\add* that you, yourself killed Yahweh’s anointed \add one\add*.”
\s1 David’s song of mourning
\s4 Full kingdom
\p
\v 17 Then David sang this funeral song for Sha’ul and his son Yonatan
\v 18 and said \add that it should be\add* taught to the \add people\add* of Yehudah. \add It’s called\add* ‘The bow’ and indeed, it’s written \add down\add* in the Book of Yashar:\x + \xo 1:18: \xt Josh 10:13.\x*
\q1
\v 19 “Yisrael’s splendour \add was\add* slain \add in the hills\add*.
\q1 How the \add powerful\add* \add warriors\add* have \add died\add*.
\q1
\v 20 Don’t tell \add them\add* in Gat.
\q1 Don’t let \add them\add* take the news to Ashkelon’s streets,
\q1 in case the Philistine \add women\add* celebrate,
\q1 and the daughters of the uncircumcised are elated.
\b
\q1
\v 21 \add You\add* mountains in Gilboa,
\q2 \add may you have\add* no dew or rain \add fall\add* on you,
\q2 nor fields \add producing grain\add* for offerings.
\q1 Because it was there that \add Shaul’s\add* shield was \add splattered with his blood\add*,
\q2 and \add the leather\add* won’t be \add preserved\add* with oil \add again\add*.
\q1
\v 22 From the blood of those slain—
\q2 from the fat of the \add warriors\add*,
\q1 Yonatan’s bow didn’t \add retreat\add*
\q2 and Sha’ul’s sword didn’t \add fail on its strikes\add*.
\b
\q1
\v 23 Sha’ul and Yonatan were loved—
\q2 they pleased the people.
\q2 and even at their death they weren’t separated.
\q1 They were swifter than eagles.
\q2 they were stronger than lions.
\b
\q1
\v 24 Weep for Sha’ul you daughters of Yisrael,
\q1 the one who \add dressed you in nice clothes with jewellery\add*,
\q1 and gave you all gold \add brooches\add* to put on.
\b
\q1
\v 25 Those warriors have fallen in the middle of the battle.
\q1 Yonatan has been killed \add there\add* on the hills.
\b
\q1
\v 26 I \add grieve\add* for you my dear friend Yonatan.
\q1 You were \add so kind\add* to me.
\q1 Your \add friendship meant more to me\add* than the women \add who say they love me\add*.
\b
\q1
\v 27 \add Yes, those\add* \add powerful warriors\add* have fallen,
\q1 and those weapons of war have \add been destroyed\add*.”
\c 2
\s1 The kingdom of David
\s4 Full kingdom
\p
\v 1 After \add that was over\add*, David inquired from Yahweh, “Should I go into one of Yehudah’s cities?”
\p “\add Yes,\add*, go,” Yahweh \add answered\add*.
\p “Where should I go?” David \add asked\add* \add again\add*.
\p “To Hebron,” he said.
\p
\v 2 \add So\add* David took his two wives (Ahinoam the Yezreelite and Abigail the \add widow\add* of Nabal the Carmelite) and went there.\x + \xo 2:2: \xt 1Sam 25:42-43.\x*
\v 3 He took his men who were with him, along with their \add families\add*, and went to live in Hebron and the \add surrounding\add* towns.
\v 4 Then the Yehudah \add leaders\add* came and anointed David as king over Yehudah.
\p They told him, “It was the men of Yabesh-Gilead who buried Sha’ul.”\x + \xo 2:4: \xt 1Sam 31:11-13.\x*
\v 5 \add So\add* David sent messengers to Yabesh-Gilead to tell them, “May Yahweh bless you all because you \add showed\add* that kindness to your master Sha’ul to bury him \add respectfully\add*.
\v 6 Now may Yahweh \add treat\add* you all with kindness and faithfulness, and I myself will also be good to you because you did that.
\v 7 \add Meanwhile\add* now that Sha’ul your master is dead, \add continue\add* to be courageous and become \add brave warriors\add* as Yehudah has anointed me as king over \add their tribe\add*.
\s1 Disputes between Sha’ul and David’s families
\s4 Full kingdom
\p
\v 8 \add However,\add* Abner (Ner’s son) who’d been Sha’ul’s army commander had taken Sha’ul’s son Iysh-Boshet\f + \fr 2:8 \ft Also known as Esh-Baal. (See 1 Chronicles 8:33.)\f* across to Mahanayim
\v 9 and \add declared\add* him to be king over Gilead, and over the Asherites and Yezreel, and over Efraim and Benyamin, and over all of Yisrael.
\v 10 Iysh-Boshet \add was forty years old\add* when he \add started to rule\add* over the \add Israelis\add*, and he \add ruled them\add* for two years.
\p But the tribe of Yehudah was loyal to David
\v 11 and \add he\add* \add ruled them\add* for seven and a half years.
\p
\v 12 \add One day\add* Abner left Mahanayim with \add some of\add* Iysh-Boshet’s servants and went to Gibeon,
\v 13 \add but\add* Yoav (Tseruyah’s son, \add traditionally called ‘Joab’ in English\add*) \add took some of\add* David’s servants and went and \add confronted\add* them at the Gibeon pool—one group on each side of the pool.
\v 14 Then Abner said to Yoav, “\add Let’s get some of these young warriors to fight it out in front of us\add*.”
\p “\add Sounds good to me\add*,” said Yoav.
\p
\v 15 \add So they stood up and counted off\add* twelve \add representing\add* Benyamin and Sha’ul’s son Iysh-Boshet and twelve from David’s servants.
\v 16 Each of them grabbed his opponent’s head and then thrust his sword into his side, so they both fell \add down\add* dead together. \add So\add* that place in Gibeon was \add named\add* ‘Helkat-Hatsurim’ \add (meaning ‘Field of Daggers’)\add*.
\p
\v 17 \add That led on to\add* a very intense battle that day, \add but\add* Abner and the Israeli men were \add defeated\add* by David’s servants.
\v 18 Tseruyah’s three sons were there: Yoav, Avishay, and Asah-El, (Asah-El was a \add fast runner\add*—like a wild antelope.)
\v 19 and Asah-El chased after Abner and \add wouldn’t give up\add*.
\v 20 Abner turned and said, “Is that you, Asah-El?”
\p “\add Yes,\add* it’s me,” he \add answered\add*.
\p
\v 21 “\add I’m warning you:\add* \add Stop chasing me and go after someone else instead\add*,” Abner \add called back\add*. But Asah-El \add wouldn’t give up\add*
\v 22 \add so\add* Abner \add tried again\add*, “\add Stop chasing me! You’ll force me to kill you\add*, then how could I face your brother Yoav?”
\v 23 \add But\add* \add Asah-El\add* \add wouldn’t give up so\add* Abner thrust the butt end of his spear into his stomach and it went right through and came out his back. He fell to the ground and died there, and \add when the others caught up, they stopped\add* there.
\p
\v 24 \add But\add* Yoav and Abishai \add kept going\add* after Abner. As the sun was setting, they came to the Ammah hill (east of Giah, along the road to the wilderness near Gibeon)
\v 25 and the \add Benyamites lined up\add* behind Abner as an \add coordinated unit\add* there on top of \add the\add* hill.
\v 26 Abner called out to Yoav, “\add Are we just going to keep killing each other\add*? Don’t you know that \add the only result can be more\add* bitterness? How long will you \add go on before you command your people to stop killing\add* their \add cousins\add*?”
\p
\v 27 “\add As God lives\add*,” Yoav \add replied\add*, “if you hadn’t \add said that\add*, then surely \add it would have been morning before they would have pulled back from the chase\add*.”
\v 28 \add So\add* Yoav had a trumpet blown and \add his\add* men \add stopped fighting and pursing the Israelis\add*.
\p
\v 29 Then Abner and his men walked all that night through the \add Jordan river plain\add*, then crossed the \add river\add* and walked all morning until they got \add back\add* to Mahanayim.
\p
\v 30 \add When\add* Yoav had assembled them all \add and counted them, only\add* Asah-El and nineteen others had been killed in the battle,
\v 31 \add although\add* \add they\add* had killed 360 of Abner’s Benyamite \add warriors\add*.
\v 32 They \add retrieved Asah-El’s body\add* and buried it in his father’s tomb in Beyt-Lehem. Then \add they\add* walked all night and got \add back\add* to Hebron \add at first\add* light.
\c 3
\p
\v 1 \add Nevertheless\add* the war between Sha’ul’s and David’s \add followers\add* dragged on and on, \add but\add* \add overall,\add* David’s \add side had more wins than the followers of Iysh-Boshet\add*.
\s1 David’s sons
\s4 Full kingdom
\p
\v 2 David’s \add wives gave birth to\add* \add six\add* sons \add while they were based there\add* in Hebron: Ahinoam (the Yezreelite) gave birth to Amnon,
\v 3 then Abigail (the \add widow\add* of Nabal the Carmelite) \add gave birth to\add* Kileab, and Maakah (daughter of King Talmai of Geshur) \add gave birth to\add* Abshalom.
\v 4 The fourth was Adoniyyah (son of Haggit), the fifth was Shefatyah (son of Abital),
\v 5 and the sixth was Yitre’am (son of David’s wife Eglah). \add All six of\add* those \add sons\add* were born to David in Hebron.
\s1 Abner switches over to David
\s4 Full kingdom
\p
\v 6 \add While the war between Sha’ul’s son Iysh-Boshet and David’s supporters continued\add*, Abner was strengthening himself with Sha’ul’s \add supporters\add*.
\v 7 \add Now\add* Sha’ul had had a slave-wife named Ritspah (daughter of Ayyah) and Abner slept with her. \add So\add* \add Iysh-Boshet\add* \add demanded\add*, “Why have you slept with my father’s slave-wife?”
\v 8 Abner \add became very angry at this challenge from Iysh-Boshet and snapped back\add*, “\add Do you think I’m Yehudah’s dog\add* \add hiding out over here\add*? Today I’ve been \add helping\add* Sha’ul’s \add family\add*: your father, his brothers, and his friends, and I won’t let you fall into David’s \add hands\add*. \add Yet\add* today you \add bring some charge against me to do with a\add* woman?
\v 9 May God punish \add me\add* if I don’t do for David exactly what Yahweh promised him
\v 10 \add and help with\add* the transfer of the kingdom away from \add your\add* family and to establish David’s \add kingdom\add* over \add both\add* Yehudah and Yisrael, from Dan \add down\add* to Beer-Sheba.”\x + \xo 3:10: \xt 1Sam 15:28.\x*
\v 11 Iysh-Boshet didn’t say a word back to Abner because he was very scared of him.
\p
\v 12 Then Abner sent messengers to David to tell \add him\add*, “Who should be king of this \add country\add*? \add Let’s come to an agreement and then I could join you\add* \add and help\add* make all of Yisrael turn to you.”
\p
\v 13 “\add Yes,\add* good,” \add David\add* \add replied\add*. “\add I’m happy to come to an agreement with you on one condition: you must bring my wife—Sha’ul’s daughter, Mikal—if you want to be accepted here\add*.”
\v 14 Then David sent messengers to Sha’ul’s son Iysh-Boshet saying, “Give \add Mikal back to\add* me. \add I earnt her as my wife with\add* the foreskins of one-hundred Philistines.”\x + \xo 3:14: \xt 1Sam 18:27.\x*
\v 15 \add So\add* Iysh-Boshet \add had her taken\add* from \add her\add* husband (Laish’s son Paltiel),
\v 16 \add but\add* he walked along behind her, weeping, as far as Bahurim \add where finally\add* Abner told him to go \add back home\add* and \add so he did\add*.
\p
\v 17 Then Abner conferred with the Israeli elders saying, “\add Previously\add* you were wanting David to be king over you,
\v 18 \add but now it’s time for action\add*. Yahweh has \add already\add* said, ‘\add I’m going to use\add* my servant David to rescue my people Yisrael from the Philistines and all their \add other\add* enemies.’ ”
\v 19 Abner also spoke \add privately with the Benyamites\add*, then he went to Hebron to tell David \add privately what the Israelis and the Benyamites had agreed to\add*.
\p
\v 20 Then Abner took twenty men and went to David at Hebron, and David put on a feast for \add all of them\add*.
\v 21 Abner \add asked\add* David, “My master, the king. Let me get \add ready\add* and go, and let me \add encourage\add* all of Yisrael that they’ll \add make an agreement\add* with you so that you will be king over \add the entire area as you’ve been wanting\add*.” \add So\add* David sent Abner, and he went in peace.
\s1 Yoav murders Abner
\s4 Full kingdom
\p
\v 22 \add Soon afterwards,\add* Yoav and some of David’s \add men\add* arrived after a raid and \add carried in\add* a lot of plunder. (Abner had already left Hebron because \add David\add* had sent him off and he’d left in peace.)
\v 23 \add When\add* Yoav and all the fighters with him arrived, \add he\add* was told that Abner had been there and spoken with the king, then sent away in peace.
\v 24 \add So Yoav\add* went to the king and \add demanded\add*, “What have you done? Abner came to you \add and I can’t believe that you’d let him go, but he’s definitely not here now\add*.
\v 25 \add Surely you realise that\add* \add he\add* \add only\add* came \add here to influence you and to find out where you’re coming from and going to, and to learn everything\add* that you’re doing?”
\p
\v 26 \add Once Yoav had finished talking to\add* David, he sent messengers \add to catch up to\add* Abner. They \add found him\add* at the Sirah cistern and brought him back \add without David’s knowledge\add*.
\v 27 \add When\add* Abner got back to Hebron, Yoav took him aside at the \add city\add* gate as if to speak to him privately, then \add stabbed\add* him in the stomach and he died \add as vengeance for killing\add* \add Yoav’s\add* brother Asah-El.
\v 28 \add Later\add* \add when\add* David heard about it, he \add declared\add*, “I and my kingdom are innocent \add of Abner’s death in Yahweh’s eyes\add*.
\v 29 \add May Yoav’s extended family continually suffer from sores or leprosy, and be forced into manual labour or be killed in battle, or run out of food to eat\add*.”
\v 30 (\add That’s how\add* Yoav and his brother Abishai murdered Abner because he’d killed their brother Asah-El in Gibeon during the war.)
\s1 Abnir’s burial
\s4 Full kingdom
\p
\v 31 Then David \add instructed\add* Yoav and all the people with him, “Tear your clothes and put on sackcloth and mourn \add for\add* Abner.” \add Later at the funeral,\add* King David walked behind the \add coffin\add*
\v 32 and they buried Abner in Hebron. The king \add cried loudly\add* at the tomb, and the people \add also\add* wept.
\v 33 The king \add sang this song\add* for Abner:
\q1 “Abner shouldn’t have died as if \add he was just some drunken fool\add*.
\q1
\v 34 \add He wasn’t handcuffed or with his feet in chains\add*.
\q1 \add He fell like someone disturbing a burglar.\add*”
\m And \add so\add* the people wept even more for him.
\p
\v 35 \add Many people brought food\add* to David during the day, but he promised, “\add May God severely punish me if I eat anything\add* before the sun goes down.”
\v 36 All the people recognised \add David’s dignity in handling this matter and were pleased with his behaviour, just as they were pleased with everything that the king did\add*,
\v 37 and \add everyone throughout Yisrael knew that the king hadn’t ordered for Abner (Ner’s son) to be executed\add*.
\v 38 Then the king told his servants, “Don’t you all \add realise that Yisrael lost a leader and a great man today\add*?
\v 39 Although I was anointed as king, I \add feel tender\add* today. Those sons of Zeruyah \add are more violent\add* than me. May Yahweh repay \add evil people appropriately for their actions\add*.”
\c 4
\s1 The murder of Iysh-Boshet
\s4 Full kingdom
\p
\v 1 \add When\add* Sha’ul’s son \add Iysh-Boshet\add* heard that Abner had \add been killed\add* in Hebron, \add he lost courage\add* and all Yisrael was horrified.
\v 2 \add He\add* had two men who were \add leaders of raiding parties\add*. They were Rimmon’s sons Baanah and Rekav from Beerot in the Benyamite region,
\v 3 \add but\add* the \add people from Beerot\add* had fled to Gittaim where they’ve stayed until now.
\p
\v 4 (Sha’ul’s son Yonatan had a son named Mefiboshet. He was \add five years old\add* when the report about Sha’ul and Yonatan’s \add death\add* came from Yezreel. \add Mefiboshet’s\add* \add nanny\add* picked him up \add to run to safety, but in her hurry\add* he fell and \add became crippled in his legs\add*.)\x + \xo 4:4: \xt 2Sam 9:3.\x*
\p
\v 5 \add One day,\add* Baanah and Rekav (the sons of Rimmon from Beerot) walked to Iysh-Boshet’s house, \add arriving in the middle of the day when he was taking a nap\add*.
\v 6-7 They entered the middle of the house \add as if getting wheat\add*, then \add entered\add* the inner room where @Iysh-Boshet was on the bed. They struck him in the \add body\add*, killing him, then they cut off his head. Then Rekav and Baanah took the head and escaped, and walked all night through the Arabah.
\v 8 They took Iysh-Boshet’s head to David at Hebron and told the king, “Look, \add here’s\add* the head of Ishbosheth, the son of your enemy Sha’ul who \add tried to kill you\add*. Today Yahweh’s given vengeance to my master the king against Sha’ul and his \add descendants\add*.”
\p
\v 9 Then David answered Rekav and his brother Baanah (the sons of Rimmon from Beerot), “\add As Yahweh lives, having\add* delivered my life from every distress,
\v 10 when the \add messenger came to Tsiklag thinking he was bringing me good news and told me that Sha’ul was dead, I had him seized and executed\add*.\x + \xo 4:10: \xt 2Sam 1:1-16.\x*
\v 11 \add Now\add* how much more when \add wicked men\add* have killed an \add innocent\add* man on his bed in his \add own\add* house. Shouldn’t I \add avenge\add* you \add two\add* \add for his murder\add* and remove you from the earth?”
\v 12 Then David commanded \add some of\add* the young men and they killed \add the two brothers\add* and cut of their hands and feet and hung \add them\add*\f + \fr 4:12 \ft It’s ambiguous in the Hebrew whether the hands and feet were strung up, or the actual bodies.\f* beside the Hebron pool, \add but\add* they took Iysh-Boshet’s head and buried it \add there\add* in Hebron in Abner’s tomb.
\c 5
\s1 David becomes king of all Israel
\s4 Full kingdom
\r (1 Chr. 11:1-9; 14:1-7)
\p
\v 1 Then \add the leaders of\add* all of Yisrael’s tribes came to David at Hebron and said to him, “Listen, we’re \add all\add* \add close relations\add*.
\v 2 \add In the past\add* when Sha’ul was \add our king\add*, you were the \add one who actually showed leadership of the people\add*. Yahweh has \add already\add* told you that you will shepherd Yisrael and become \add our king\add*.”
\v 3 \add So with Yahweh as their witness,\add* all the Israeli elders made a \add formal agreement\add* with David, and they anointed him as king over \add all\add* Yisrael.
\v 4 David \add was thirty years old\add* when he became \add their\add* king and he reigned for \add a total of\add* forty years:\x + \xo 5:4-5: \xt 1Ki 2:11; 1Ch 3:4; 29:27.\x*
\v 5 seven and a half years in Hebron as king of Yehudah, then thirty-three years in Yerushalem as king over all Yisrael and Yehudah.
\s1 David captures Yerushalem
\s4 Full kingdom
\p
\v 6 The king and his men \add battled\add* against the Yebusites who lived \add in and around\add* Yerushalem, \add but\add* \add Yebusites\add* \add mocked\add* David, “You’ll \add never break in here—even blind and crippled men could keep you out\add*,” because they thought that David couldn’t get in.\x + \xo 5:6: \xt Josh 15:63; Jdg 1:21.\x*
\v 7 \add But\add* David \em did\em* capture that Tsiyyon stronghold that \add then became known as\add* David’s city.
\p
\v 8 He’d told \add his men\add* that day, “Anyone \add wanting to\add* strike the Yebusites \add should use the water tunnel to reach\add* the lame people and the blind people—the ones who are hated by David.” (That’s why they say that blind and crippled people shouldn’t enter the house.\f + \fr 5:8 \ft Left ambiguous here because it’s not clear from the Hebrew. (Some think ‘David’s palace’ while others go for ‘God’s temple’.)\f*)
\p
\v 9 \add So\add* David lived in that stronghold and called it ‘David’s city’—\add expanding it on all sides\add*.
\v 10 David \add continued to grow more powerful because\add* Yahweh the commander God was with him.
\p
\v 11 King Hiram from Tyre sent messengers to David, then he sent \add carpenters and stone-cutters\add* to build a \add palace\add* for David.
\p
\v 12 David knew that Yahweh had established him as king over \add all\add* Yisrael and that he \add was prospering\add* the kingdom for the sake of his people the Israelis.
\p
\v 13 \add After David moved from Hebron to\add* Yerushalem, he \add married more wives and took more slave-wives, all of whom produced more sons and daughters for him\add*.
\v 14 The names of his sons who were born in Yerushalem were Shammua, Shobab, Natan \add (Nathan)\add*, Shelomoh \add (Solomon)\add*,
\v 15 Ibhar, Elishua, Nefeg, Yafia,
\v 16 Elishama, Eliada, and Elifelet.
\s1 Defeated by David the Philistines
\s4 Full kingdom
\r (1 Chr. 14:8-17)
\p
\v 17 \add When\add* the Philistines heard that David had been \add proclaimed\add* as king over \add all\add* Yisrael, \add their army set off to capture\add* \add him\add*, \add but\add* David heard and \add retreated\add*\f + \fr 5:17 \ft The Hebrew says ‘descended’, but doesn’t tell us either from where (probably Yerushalem) or to where (possibly Masada).\f* to the stronghold.
\v 18 The Philistines \add moved in\add* and took over the Rafa valley,
\v 19 and David inquired from Yahweh, “Should I \add attack\add* the Philistines? Will you \add help me defeat them\add*?”
\p “\add Yes,\add* \add attack them\add*,” Yahweh \add replied\add*, “because I’ll certainly \add help you to defeat them\add*.”
\p
\v 20 \add So\add* David \add attacked\add* and \add defeated\add* them, and said, “Yahweh broke through my enemies \add in front of me like breaking a dam\add*.” So he called the place ‘Baal-Peratsim’ \add (which means ‘Master of breaking through’)\add*.
\v 21 \add The Philistines\add* left their idols there, and David and his men \add took them away\add*.
\p
\v 22 Then the Philistines \add returned to\add* the Rafa valley and took over it again.
\v 23 \add Again\add* David inquired from Yahweh who \add replied\add*, “\add No,\add* \add don’t go straight in. Move\add* around behind them and \add then attack\add* them from opposite the trees.
\v 24 Then when you hear a sound in the tops of the trees \add that sounds like marching, then you’ll know that Yahweh has gone ahead\add* to strike the Philistines’ camp.”
\v 25 \add So\add* David \add followed Yahweh’s instructions\add* \add they\add* attacked the Philistines from Geva \add all the way\add* to Gezer.
\c 6
\s1 The Box with the agreement is brought to Yerushalem
\s4 Full kingdom
\r (1 Chr. 13:1-14; 15:25–16:6,43)
\p
\v 1 Then David \add selected thirty thousand Israeli warriors and gathered them together\add*.
\v 2 \add He led them to\add* \add Kiriat-Yearim (formerly called\add* Baalah) in Yehudah to get the box of God (whose name is Yahweh the army commander) who lives between the two winged creatures on the top of it.\x + \xo 6:2: \xt Exo 25:22.\x*
\v 3 They \add placed the sacred chest\add* on a \add newly-made\add* cart and started moving it from Abinadab’s house which was on a hill. Uzzah and Ahyo (Abinadab’s sons) were leading the cart.\x + \xo 6:3: \xt 1Sam 7:1-2.\x*
\v 4 They took it from Abinadab’s house and Ahyo \add took the lead in front\add*.
\v 5 David and all the \add Israelis\add* were celebrating \add in God’s presence\add* with \add wooden\add* harps and lyres, along with tambourines, shakers, and cymbals.
\p
\v 6 \add But\add* when they reached Nakon’s threshing floor the oxen \add stumbled so\add* Uzzah reached out \add to steady the sacred chest\add*.
\v 7 Yahweh \add became furious with\add* Uzzah and \add killed\add* him \add right\add* there by the \add sacred chest because he’d touched it\add*.
\v 8 \add Now\add* David \add got angry\add* because of Yahweh’s outburst against Uzzah, and that place has been called Perets-Uzzah \add (meaning ‘The punishment of Uzzah’)\add* until today.
\v 9 David was afraid of Yahweh that day and asked, “How will Yahweh’s box \add get to Yerushalem\add*?”
\v 10 \add So\add* \add he\add* \add decided not to take\add* Yahweh’s box \add there\add* and \add redirected\add* it \add instead\add* to the house of Obed-Edom (a Gittite).
\v 11 The \add sacred chest\add* stayed at Obed-Edom’s house for three months, and Yahweh blessed him and all \add the household\add*.\x + \xo 6:11: \xt 1Ch 26:4-5.\x*
\p
\v 12 \add Someone told\add* King David, “Yahweh has blessed Obed-Edom’s \add household\add* because of the \add sacred chest,” so\add* David went and brought God’s Box from Obed-Edom’s house to \add Yerushalem with much happiness\add*.
\v 13 \add When the men who were carrying the sacred chest had walked\add* six steps, they stopped and \add David\add* sacrificed a \add bull and a fattened calf\add* \add there\add*.
\v 14 Then David, wearing a linen \add apron\add*, danced \add in front of\add* Yahweh, \add putting everything into it\add*.
\v 15 David and all the \add Israelis\add* brought the \add sacred chest\add* \add into Yerushalem\add* with shouting and trumpet \add blasts\add*.
\p
\v 16 \add However\add*, as they were entering the city, \add David’s\add* wife Mikal (Sha’ul’s daughter) looked out the window and saw King David leaping and dancing \add in front of\add* Yahweh, and she \add felt only despite for\add* him.
\v 17 They took Yahweh’s box and placed it in the middle of the tent that David had erected for it. Then David \add offered burnt sacrifices\add* to Yahweh, as well as peace offerings.
\v 18 \add When\add* David \add had finished offering those sacrifices\add*, he blessed the people in commander Yahweh’s name.
\v 19 He \add handed out a large bread roll\add*, a cake of \add pressed\add* dates, and a cake of \add pressed\add* raisins to each man and woman \add there\add*, then they all returned to their homes.\x + \xo 6:19-20: \xt 1Ch 16:43.\x*
\p
\v 20 Then David returned to bless his \add own\add* house, \add but his wife Mikal came\add* out to meet him \add complaining, “What disgraceful behaviour for Yisrael’s king today—dancing when he was wearing so little and exposing himself to his female servants like some brainless person\add*!”
\p
\v 21 “\add It was to thank\add* Yahweh,” David \add responded\add*, “who chose me (rather than your father and any of his family) by appointing me as leader over Yahweh’s people Yisrael. I was celebrating \add in front\add* of Yahweh
\v 22 and I will humiliate and \add humble myself\add* \add even\add* more than that. \add Yet\add* I will \add end up\add* being honoured by those female servants \add that you were talking about\add*.”
\p
\v 23 \add After that,\add* Sha’ul’s daughter Mikal \add never had any more children\add*.
\c 7
\s1 Yahweh’s promise to David
\s4 Full kingdom
\r (1 Chr. 17:1-15)
\p
\v 1 Then the king \add moved into his palace\add*, and Yahweh \add allowed him to have a time of peace\add* from all his enemies.
\v 2 \add One day\add* the king said to the prophet Natan, “Look, I’m \add here\add* living in a house \add made\add* of cedar, but God’s box is \add still there in a tent\add*.”
\p
\v 3 “Go and do \add whatever you consider best\add*,” Natan \add replied\add*, “because Yahweh is with you.”
\v 4 \add But that\add* night, Yahweh \add spoke\add* to Natan,
\v 5 “Go and tell my servant David that Yahweh says, ‘Will you build a house for me \add to live in\add*?
\v 6 I haven’t lived in a house since I brought the \add Israelis\add* out of Egypt \add right up until now\add*, \add but rather\add* I was living in a tent \add as they moved around\add*.
\v 7 In \add all those places, I never once queried the leaders to ask\add* why they never built a cedar house for me.’
\p
\v 8 “\add But\add* now you should tell my servant David that commander Yahweh says, ‘I myself took you out of the \add grass field where you looked after the sheep and goats\add* to become the leader of my people the \add Israelis\add*.
\v 9 Everywhere you’ve gone, I’ve been with you and \add destroyed your enemies in front of you\add*, and I will make you \add famous like all the famous\add* people on the earth.
\v 10 I will \add establish\add* a place for the \add Israelis\add* and put them there to live, and they won’t \add be afraid because evil people\add* won’t continue to oppress them \add like happened in the past\add*
\v 11 \add when I appointed heroes\add* \add (traditionally ‘judges’)\add* over my people Yisrael. I will give you \add peace\add* from all your enemies, and I, Yahweh, will \add enable your descendants to rule after you\add*.
\v 12 \add when your time on earth comes to an end\add* and you’re laid down with your ancestors, I will appoint one of your sons to be king and I will establish his kingdom.\x + \xo 7:12: \xt Psa 89:3-4; 132:11; Yhn 7:42; Acts 2:30.\x*
\v 13 He’s \add the one who’ll build a temple for me\add*, and I will \add make his descendents reign\add* forever.
\v 14 I myself will become like a father to him, and he’ll become like a son to me. When he \add disobeys, I’ll punish him like fathers punish their sons\add*.\x + \xo 7:14: \xt Psa 89:26-27; 2Cor 6:18; Heb 1:5.\x*
\v 15 \add But\add* my kindness won’t turn away from you like I turned away from Sha’ul—\add the one who I removed ahead of you\add*.
\v 16 Your \add descendants\add* and your kingdom will remain forever. Your throne will be established forever.’ ”\x + \xo 7:16: \xt Psa 89:36-37.\x*
\s1 David’s prayer
\s4 Full kingdom
\r (1 Chr. 17:16-27)
\p
\v 17 \add So\add* Natan \add passed all of that onto\add* David,
\v 18 and King David went and sat \add in front\add* of Yahweh and said, “Who am I, my master Yahweh, and \add how important is my family\add* that you have brought me to \add this point\add*?
\v 19 \add But that was just minor to you,\add* my master Yahweh. You also spoke about \add the distant future for my descendants\add*.
\v 20 What more can \add I,\add* David say to you? \add But\add* my master Yahweh, you yourself know your servant.
\v 21 You’ve done all these incredible things \add in order to fulfil what you said and to fulfil your own desires\add*, and then \add revealed them to\add* your servant.
\v 22 That’s why you’re incredible, Yahweh my God, \add and so\add* there’s no one like you. There’s no God except you—\add that’s what we keep hearing about\add*.
\v 23 \add What other nation\add* is like your people, Yisrael—one nation on the earth that \add you\add* went to redeem for \add yourself\add* as a people—\add rescuing\add* you from Egypt and its gods? \add You\add* \add made a reputation for yourself\add* and \add did amazing and scary things for your nation in front\add* of your people\x + \xo 7:23: \xt Deu 4:34.\x*
\v 24 You established \add us\add* Israelis as your \add own\add* people forever, and you yourself Yahweh became \add our\add* God.
\p
\v 25 “And now, Yahweh God, the \add promise you made\add* concerning your servant and his \add descendants\add*, and do just as you have spoken and \add make it come true into the future\add*.
\v 26 May your \add reputation be good\add* forever, \add with people\add* saying, ‘Commander Yahweh is God over Yisrael,’ and the \add dynasty\add* of your servant David will be established \add under you\add*.
\v 27 For you, commander Yahweh are Yisrael’s God. You have \add told\add* your servant, ‘I will build a \add dynasty\add* for you.’ \add That’s why\add* your servant has found \add the courage\add* to pray this prayer.
\p
\v 28 “\add So\add* now, my master Yahweh, you are God, and \add you do what you say\add*, and you have said these good things concerning your servant.
\v 29 Now, \add if it pleases you,\add* bless your servant’s \add extended family\add* forever, because you yourself, my master Yahweh, have spoken, and from your blessing, your servant’s \add family\add* will be blessed forever.”
\c 8
\s1 David’s victories
\s4 Full kingdom
\r (1 Chr. 18:1-17)
\p
\v 1 \add Sometime later,\add* David \add attacked\add* the Philistines and \add defeated\add* them, and he \add captured\add* Meteg-Ammah from \add them\add*.
\p
\v 2 Then he \add defeated\add* the \add Moabites\add*. \add David\add* forced them to lie on the ground and \add used a length of rope to decide their fate—those inside two lengths of the rope were killed, and those inside the third length were spared\add* and \add so\add* the Moabites became David’s servants—bringing him tribute.
\p
\v 3 Then David \add defeated\add* Tsovah’s King Hadadezer (son of Rehov) \add who had tried to reestablish his authority over the Euphrates\add* River.
\v 4 David captured 1,700 horsemen and twenty thousand men on foot. \add He\add* hamstrung all the chariot \add horses\add* except for a hundred of them.
\p
\v 5 Then \add the Arameans\add* came from Damascus to help Tsovah’s king Hadadezer \add but\add* David \add killed\add* twenty-two thousand \add of them\add*.
\v 6 David \add stationed\add* garrisons in Aram (in Damascus) and \add the Arameans\add* became David’s servants—bringing him tribute, and Yahweh \add helped\add* David \add win\add* wherever he went.
\v 7 David \add confiscated\add* the gold shields that Hadadezer’s servants carried and brought them to Yerushalem.
\v 8 \add He\add* also brought a large amount of bronze out of Hadadezer’s cities of Betah and Berotay.
\p
\v 9 \add When\add* Hamat’s King Toi heard that David had \add defeated\add* Hadadezer’s entire army,
\v 10 \add he\add* sent his son Yoram to ask for peace \add for Hamat\add* and to \add congratulate\add* him for fighting Hadadezer and \add defeating\add* him because Hadadezer \add often battled against\add* Toi. \add Yoram\add* \add brought containers with him, made\add* of gold, silver, and bronze.
\v 11 King David \add dedicated\add* them to Yahweh, \add along\add* with the silver and gold \add that he’d taken\add* from all the nations that \add they’d conquered\add*:
\v 12 from Aram and Moab, from the \add Ammonites\add* and the Philistines, and from Amalak and from the plunder of Tsovah’s King Hadadezer (son of Rehov).
\p
\v 13 Then David made \add more of\add* a name \add for himself\add* when he returned from \add defeating eighteen thousand Arameans\add* in the Salt Valley.\x + \xo 8:13: \xt Psa 60 header.\x*
\v 14 He \add stationed\add* garrisons \add throughout\add* Edom and \add made the people\add* his servants, and Yahweh \add protected\add* David wherever \add they fought\add*.
\p
\v 15 \add So\add* David \add reigned\add* over all Yisrael and \add led all his people with\add* justice and \add integrity\add*.
\v 16 Tseruyah’s son Yoav was the army \add commander\add* and Ahilud’s son Yehoshafat was the secretary.
\v 17 The priests were Ahitub’s son Tsadok and Evyatar’s son Ahimelek, and Serayah was secretary.
\v 18 Yehoyada’s son Benayah \add supervised\add* the Keretites and the Peletites \add (David’s bodyguard)\add*, and David’s sons were \add his\add* \add administrators\add*.
\c 9
\s1 David assists Mefiboshet
\s4 Full kingdom
\p
\v 1 \add One day\add* David \add asked\add*, “Is there still anyone remaining from Sha’ul’s \add extended family because I’d like to show kindness to them\add* for Yonatan’s sake?”\x + \xo 9:1: \xt 1Sam 20:15-17.\x*
\p
\v 2 \add Now\add* there was a servant in Sha’ul household named Tsiva and he was summoned to David, and the king \add asked\add* him, “Are you Tsiva?”
\p “\add Yes, I’m\add* your servant,” he \add replied\add*.
\p
\v 3 “Is there \add anyone from Sha’ul’s family who’s still alive\add*?” the king \add asked\add*. “\add If so,\add* I’d \add like to show God’s kindness to them\add*.”\x + \xo 9:3: \xt 2Sam 4:4.\x*
\p “\add Yes,\add* \add There’s still one of Yonatan’s sons alive\add*,” Tsiva told the king. “\add He’s crippled in both legs\add*.”
\p
\v 4 “Where is he?” the king asked.
\p “\add Actually,\add*” Tsiva told the king, “he’s at Makir’s house—the son of Ammiel in Lo-Debar.”
\v 5 \add So\add* King David sent messengers to Lo-Debar to have him brought \add to Yerushalem\add*.
\p
\v 6 Then Yonatan’s son Mefiboshet came to David and fell onto \add his knees and bowed his face down to the ground\add*, and David said, Mefiboshet.”
\p “I’m your servant,” he \add replied\add*.
\p
\v 7 Then David told him, “Don’t be afraid, because I’ll certainly \add show you\add* kindness for the sake of your father Yonatan. I’ll restore all the pastureland that belonged to your grandfather Sha’ul, and you yourself \add are invited to always eat at\add* my table.”
\p
\v 8 \add Mefiboshet\add* \add bowed low and asked\add*, “Your servant’s \add nothing more than a\add* dead dog. \add Why would you care about\add* me?”
\p
\v 9 Then the king summoned Sha’ul’s servant Tsiva and told him, “I’ve given everything that belonged to Sha’ul and to all his \add household\add* to your master.
\v 10 You and your fifteen sons and your twenty servants must work the land for him and \add harvest the produce to support\add* your master’s \add grand\add*son, but \add he\add* will eat \add with me at my house\add*.”
\p
\v 11 “\add Yes,\add* my master the king,” Tsiva \add responded\add*. “Your servant will do everything you’ve commanded.”
\p \add So from then on,\add* Mefiboshet always ate at the king’s table as if he was one of the king’s sons.
\v 12 Mefiboshet had a young son named Mika. All \add Tsiva’s household\add* became Mefiboshet’s servants,
\v 13 \add but\add* Mefiboshet (who was crippled in both legs) lived in Yerushalem because he \add had a permanent invitation to eat with the king\add*.
\c 10
\s1 Yisrael defeats the Ammonites and the Arameans
\s4 Full kingdom
\r (1 Chr. 19:1-19)
\p
\v 1 \add Some time later,\add* the \add Ammonite\add* king died, and his son Hanun replace him as king.
\v 2 “I’ll be kind to Nahash’s son Hanun,” David said, “just like his father was kind to me.” So \add he\add* sent servants \add to Hanun\add* \add to convey his condolences\add*.
\p \add When\add* \add they\add* \add arrived in the Ammon region\add*,
\v 3 the \add Ammonite commanders\add* said to their master Hanun, “\add Do you think that David really sent condolences to honour your late father\add*? Isn’t it \add more likely\add* \add because he wanted them to spy on us, and to explore the city so he could more easily conquer it\add*?”
\p
\v 4 \add So\add* Hanun \add seized\add* David’s servants and had half of their beards shaved off and their robes cut in half \add all the way\add* up to their buttocks, then he sent them off.
\v 5 They \add sent messengers ahead\add* to tell David because they were very humiliated, and the king told them to stay in Yeriho before returning when their beards grew back.
\p
\v 6 Then the \add Ammonite leaders realised that they’d now caused David to despise them, so\add* they hired twenty thousand \add Aramean\add* \add (or Syrian)\add* \add mercenaries\add* from Beyt-Rehob and Tsovah, and \add another\add* one thousand from Maakah and twelve thousand from Tov.
\v 7 \add When\add* David heard \add that\add*, he sent Yoav in with the entire army.
\v 8 The \add Ammonites\add* came out the \add city\add* gate and \add organised themselves for battle at the entrance\add*, while \add their hired mercenaries stood apart out in the countryside\add*.
\p
\v 9 \add When Yoav saw that he was disadvantaged with enemy lines both in front\add* and behind, he \add selected certain Israeli warriors\add* and placed them to battle the \add Aramean mercenaries\add*,
\v 10 leaving the others to face the Ammonites under the command of his brother Avishay,
\v 11 telling him, “If \add the Arameans\add* are too strong for me, then you come \add and rescue us, but\add* if the \add Ammonites\add* are too strong for you, then I’ll \add come and rescue\add* you.
\v 12 Be strong and courageous for \add the sake of\add* our people and our God’s cities, and Yahweh will do \add whatever he considers right\add*.”
\p
\v 13 \add So\add* Yoav and \add his men advanced to attack the Aramean mercenaries but they fled away from them\add*.
\v 14 \add When the Ammonites saw the Arameans running away, they started retreating from Abishai and went back into\add* the city, \add so\add* Yoav \add withdrew from attacking the Ammonites and returned\add* to Yerushalem.
\p
\v 15 \add When the Arameans realised that they’d been defeated by\add* Yisrael, they assembled \add all their warriors\add* together \add again\add*.
\v 16 \add King\add* Hadadezer \add (from Tsovah)\add* \add called for Aramean warriors\add* from beyond the \add Euphrates\add* River and they came to Heylam. Shovak was Hadadezer’s army commander.
\v 17 \add When\add* David \add heard that\add*, he assembled all \add the Israeli warriors\add* and they crossed the Yordan \add going towards\add* Helam. \add The Arameans came out\add* to meet David and \add the two sides fought each other\add*.
\v 18 \add But\add* \add again\add* \add the Arameans\add* fled from \add the Israelis\add*, and David killed seven hundred \add Aramean charioteers\add* and forty thousand cavalry, and their commander Shobak was struck and died there \add also\add*.
\v 19 Then all the kings \add associated with Hadadezer realised they couldn’t defeat\add* Yisrael, \add so\add* they made peace with \add the Israelis\add* and served them, and \add so\add* the Arameans were afraid to \add try to\add* rescue the \add Ammonites\add* again.
\c 11
\s1 David takes Uriyyah’s wife
\s4 Full kingdom
\p
\v 1 \add The next spring (when kings usually go to war)\add*, David sent Yoav and his \add officials\add* and all the \add Israeli warriors\add*, and they \add defeated the Ammonites and besieged\add* Rabbah.\x + \xo 11:1: \xt 1Ch 20:1.\x*
\p \add But\add* David stayed in Yerushalem,
\v 2 and \add early one\add* evening \add he\add* got up from \add a nap\add* and walked around the \add palace roof area\add*. From \add there\add* he saw a woman bathing, and she was very \add good-looking\add*.
\v 3 David sent \add a messenger\add* \add to find out who she was, and was told\add*, “That’s Eliam’s daughter Batsheva—Uriyyah the Hittite’s wife.”
\v 4 Then \add he\add* sent messengers \add to get\add* her, and she came and he slept with her. (She had been \add purifying herself after the completion of her menstrual period\add*.) Then she returned to her house.
\p
\v 5 \add After some time,\add* the woman \add realised that she\add* was pregnant, and \add so\add* she informed David.
\v 6 David sent to Yoav, “Send Uriyyah the Hittite \add here\add* to me.” \add So\add* Yoav sent Uriyyah to David.
\v 7 \add When he arrived, David asked him about how Yoav and his men were doing, and how the battle was going\add*,
\v 8 then \add he\add* told \add him\add*, “Go to your house and \add relax\add*.” \add So\add* Uriyyah \add left the palace\add* and the king \add sent a gift to be delivered to his house\add*.
\v 9 \add But\add* Uriyyah didn’t go home—\add instead he slept at the palace entrance\add* with all the king’s servants,
\v 10 \add The next day,\add* David was informed that Uriyyah didn’t go home to his house, \add so\add* \add he\add* \add asked\add* \add him\add*, “\add Didn’t you just get back from a long journey\add*? Why didn’t you go \add home\add*?”
\p
\v 11 “The \add sacred chest\add* and \add the warriors from\add* Yisrael and Yehudah are living in tents,” Uriyyah \add replied\add*. “And my master, Yoav, and my master’s servants are camping \add out in the open\add*. \add So I couldn’t just\add* go to my house to eat and to drink and to sleep with my wife. By your life and by the life of your spirit, I \add couldn’t do that\add*.”
\p
\v 12 “\add Well,\add* stay here today also,” David told \add him\add*, “and tomorrow I’ll send you \add back\add*.” \add So\add* Uriyyah stayed in Yerushalem that day and the following day,
\v 13 and David \add summoned\add* him \add over\add*, and they ate and drank together, and \add David\add* got him drunk. \add But even then\add*, \add Uriyyah\add* didn’t go back to his house, but when he left in the evening he went \add back\add* to sleep \add in the dorm\add* with his master’s servants.
\p
\v 14 \add The next morning\add*, David wrote a \add note\add* to Yoav and \add told\add* Uriyyah \add to deliver it\add*.
\v 15 He’d written, “\add Place\add* Uriyyah in the front \add where the fighting is\add* strongest, then \add fall\add* back from behind him so that he’ll be struck and die.”
\v 16 \add So\add* as Yoav \add was surrounding\add* the city, he \add placed\add* Uriyyah where he knew \add the strongest enemy warriors\add* \add would be fighting\add*.
\v 17 The \add warriors\add* from the city came out and fought against Yoav’s \add men\add*, and some of David’s servants \add were killed\add* and \add so was\add* Uriyyah.
\p
\v 18 Then Yoav sent \add a messenger\add* to David \add to give him a full account of the battle\add*.
\v 19 He told the messenger, “\add Once you’ve finished telling all the details of the battle\add* to the king,
\v 20 if \add he\add* gets angry and \add asks\add*, ‘Why did you all \add go so close in\add* to the city to fight? Didn’t you know that they’d shoot \add down\add* from the wall?
\v 21 \add Wasn’t Yerub-Beshet’s son Abimilek killed by a woman in Tevets\add* when she threw a millstone down from the wall? Why did you approach the wall?’ Then you should say, ‘Your servant Uriyyah the Hittite is also dead.’ ”\x + \xo 11:21: \xt Jdg 9:53.\x*
\p
\v 22 \add So\add* the messenger left and went and told David everything that Yoav had told him,
\v 23 saying, “\add Their men gained ground and came out against us in the countryside, but we forced them back to their city\add* gate.
\v 24 Then \add their\add* archers were shooting at your men from \add the top of\add* the wall and \add some of your men were killed, including\add* your servant Uriyyah the Hittite.”
\p
\v 25 David \add sent the messenger back to encourage Yoav\add*, “Don’t let \add yourself be upset by what happened\add* because \add no one knows who might die in a battle\add*. \add Reinforce your battle\add* against the city and tear it down.”
\p
\v 26 \add When Uriyyah’s wife Batsheva heard that her husband had been killed\add*, she mourned for \add him\add*.
\v 27 \add When her time of mourning was over\add*, David sent for her and brought her to \add the palace\add*. She became a wife to him and bore a son for him, \add but Yahweh was unhappy about what\add* David had done.
\c 12
\s1 Natan brings rebuke to David
\s4 Full kingdom
\p
\v 1 \add So\add* Yahweh sent Natan to David \add to tell\add* him, “\add Once\add* \add there was a rich man and a poor man living in the same city\add*.\x + \xo 12:1: \xt Psa 51 header.\x*
\v 2 The rich man \add had a large number\add* of flocks and herds,
\v 3 \add but\add* the poor man only had one little female lamb that he’d bought. It grew up with him and his sons, and would eat his left-overs and drink from his cup and lay down in his lap—it was like a daughter to him.
\v 4 \add One day\add* the rich man \add had a visitor, but instead of taking one of his own animals for a meal, he killed the poor man’s lamb and prepared it for the meal for his guest\add*.”
\p
\v 5 David \add got very angry listening to that\add* and told Natan, “By the life of Yahweh, the man that did that \add definitely deserves to be put to\add* death!
\v 6 He must \add pay back four lambs\add* for doing that and for \add having no pity\add* \add on that poor man\add*.”
\p
\v 7 Then Natan said to David, “You are \add that rich\add* man. Yahweh, the God of Yisrael, says to you: ‘I myself anointed you as king over Yisrael, and I myself \add kept you safe from\add* Sha’ul.
\v 8 I gave you the house that belonged to your master, \add as well as\add* his wives. I \add made you king over\add* \add both\add* Yisrael and Yehudah. And \add if that wasn’t enough, I’ve given you more and more\add*.
\v 9 \add So\add* why have you despised \add my commands\add* by doing \add what you knew was evil\add*? You had Uriyyah the Hittite killed with \add an Ammonite sword\add* and you took his wife for yourself.
\v 10 \add So\add* now, because you despised me and took Uriyyah’s wife as your own, \add war and violence will never go away from you and your descendants\add*.
\v 11 \add I will cause a disaster to hit you from within your own household—I’ll take your wives and give them to a family member right in front of your eyes, and he will let everyone know that he’s sleeping\add* with your wives.\x + \xo 12:11-12: \xt 2Sam 16:22.\x*
\v 12 \add You did what you did\add* in secret, \add but\add* I myself will do all this \add in public\add* before all Yisrael.’”
\p
\v 13 “\add Yes,\add* I’ve sinned against Yahweh,” David \add responded\add* to Natan.
\p “Yahweh has taken away your sin,” Natan \add replied\add*. “You won’t die.
\v 14 Nevertheless, because you have utterly disrespected Yahweh in this matter, also your \add new\add* son is certainly going to die.”
\v 15 Then Natan went home.
\s1 David’s son dies
\s4 Full kingdom
\p Then Yahweh \add caused the baby (that Uriyyah’s wife had given birth to) to\add* get sick.
\v 16 David \add pleaded with\add* Yahweh for the boy’s sake, and he fasted, and he spent the \add entire\add* night lying down on the ground.
\v 17 The \add influential members\add* of his household got beside him to try to get him up from the ground, but he \add wouldn’t budge\add*, and he wouldn’t eat \add anything they brought\add*.
\v 18 Then on the seventh day, the baby died, \add but\add* David’s servants were afraid to tell him because \add after seeing his response when the child was sick, they were afraid of what he might do to himself when he found out that his son\add* had died.
\p
\v 19 \add However, when\add* David noticed his servants whispering together, he \add realised that the baby must have died, and he asked\add* \add them\add*, “Did the baby die?”
\p “\add Yes,\add*” they \add answered\add*, “he \add passed away\add*.”
\p
\v 20 Then David got up from the ground and washed, and he \add rubbed lotions on\add* and changed his clothes, then he entered Yahweh’s \add tent and worshipped him\add*. Then he \add went back home and asked for food to be served\add*, and he ate.
\p
\v 21 His servants \add queried\add* him, “\add We don’t understand what just happened: when the baby was alive you fasted and wept, but yet when he dies, you get up and have a meal?\add*”
\p
\v 22 “While the child was still alive,” David \add replied\add*, “I fasted and I wept, because I \add thought\add*, ‘Who knows? Yahweh might be gracious to me and let \add him\add* live.’
\v 23 \add But\add* now \add that\add* he’s dead, \add there’s no more reason\add* to fast—I can’t bring him back again. \add One day\add* I’ll go to him, \add but\add* he’ll \add never\add* come back \add here\add* to me.”
\v 24 Then David comforted his wife Batsheva.
\s1 The birth of Shelomoh
\s4 Full kingdom
\p Then \add David\add* went to \add Batsheva\add* and \add slept\add* with her, and \add in due course\add* she \add gave birth\add* to a son. \add David\add* he named him Shelomoh \add (Solomon)\add*, and Yahweh loved \add that boy\add*
\v 25 and sent the prophet Natan to name him Yedidyah\f + \fr 12:25 \ft That name didn’t seem to stick because this is the only mention of it in the Bible.\f* \add (which means ‘loved by Yahweh’)\add* for Yahweh’s sake.
\s1 David captures Rabbah
\s4 Full kingdom
\r (1 Chr. 20:1-3)
\p
\v 26 Then Yoav fought \add the Ammonites\add* at Rabbah and captured \add their\add* \add palace\add*,
\v 27 then \add he\add* sent messengers to David to tell him, “I’ve fought against Rabbah \add and\add* I’ve overthrown the \add city’s water supply\add*.
\v 28 \add So\add* now, gather the rest of \add our fighters\add* and lay siege to the city and capture it. Otherwise I’ll \add do it\add* and then \add it’ll be named after me\add*.
\v 29 \add So\add* David gathered all his warriors and went to Rabbah, \add where\add* he attacked \add the city\add* and captured it.
\v 30 \add He\add* took the king’s crown off his head (it was gold and weighed around 30kg), and \add it was placed\add* on \add his\add* head. \add A lot of other plunder was also taken from\add* the city.
\v 31 The inhabitants of \add Rabbah\add* were brought out and \add assigned to work at the brick kiln\add* with saws, iron picks, and axes. (He did that to all the \add Ammonite\add* cities.) Then David and all his people returned to Yerushalem.
\c 13
\s1 Amnon rapes Tamar
\s4 Full kingdom
\p
\v 1 \add Some time afterwards,\add* David’s son Amnon \add fell in love with his beautiful half-sister\add* Tamar (Abshalom’s sister),
\v 2 and \add he\add* \add made himself frustrated,\add* \add always thinking about her\add* because she was a virgin. However, \add he\add* \add couldn’t do anything with her\add*.
\v 3 \add But\add* Amnon had a very shrewd friend called Yonadab (son of David’s brother Shimeah)
\v 4 and \add Yonadab\add* \add asked\add* him, “\add Hey,\add* \add you’re a son of the king, so tell me why you’re always so unhappy\add*?”
\p “I’m in love with my brother Abshalom’s sister Tamar,” Amnon \add replied\add*.
\p
\v 5 “\add Go to bed\add* and pretend to be sick,” Yonadab \add suggested\add*. “Then \add when\add* your father comes to see you, \add ask\add* him, ‘Please let my sister Tamar come \add to look after my food. She can cook it here and serve it to me\add*.’ ”
\v 6 \add So\add* Amnon lay down and pretended to be sick, and \add when\add* the king came to see him, Amnon \add asked\add* \add him\add*, “Please, let my sister Tamar come and make a couple of bread rolls \add while I’m watching, and then she can serve them to me\add*.”
\p
\v 7 \add So\add* David sent \add a message\add* to Tamar \add to ask her to\add* go to her brother Amnon’s house and prepare food for him.
\v 8 \add So\add* Tamar went to her half-brother Amnon’s house where he was lying down. She took \add some\add* dough and kneaded it into breadrolls and baked them.
\v 9 Then she took the tray \add over to him\add*, but he refused to eat, saying, “\add Send everyone else out of here\add*,” \add so they all left\add*.
\v 10 Then Amnon told Tamar, “Bring the food into the bedroom so that \add you can serve it to me\add*.” \add So\add* Tamar took the breadrolls that she’d made, and took them to Amnon in the bedroom.
\v 11 \add But when she got close enough to him,\add* he grabbed her and insisted, “Come \add and\add* lie down with me, my sister.”
\p
\v 12 “No, my brother,” she told him, “don’t humiliate me because \add we Israelis don’t do that\add*. Don’t do this disgraceful thing.
\v 13 Where \add could I hide my shame\add*? And you—you’d be \add considered\add* a godless fool in Yisrael. \add Just speak to the king because he’d give me to you to marry\add*.”
\v 14 \add But he didn’t want her advice, and being\add* stronger than her, he humiliated her \add by forcing her down and raping\add* her.
\p
\v 15 \add Instantly,\add* Amnon hated her with terrible hatred—a much greater hatred than the love with which he’d loved her, and \add he\add* told her to get up and get out.
\p
\v 16 “No, \add no\add*.” she responded. “\add Sending me away would be even worse than what you just\add* did to me.”
\p \add But\add* he refused to listen to her
\v 17 and called his \add personal servant\add*. He told him to \add take\add* the woman away and send her outside and then lock the door behind her.
\v 18 (She was wearing the kind of long robe that the virgin daughters of the king wore as an outer garment.)
\p \add So the servant pushed\add* her outside and locked the door behind her.
\v 19 Then Tamar put ashes on her head and tore the long robe that she was wearing. She put her hand on her head and wailed as she walked \add home\add*.\f + \fr 13:19 \ft The ashes, tearing of clothes, putting hand on head, and wailing, were all cultural signs of mourning and distress.\f*
\v 20 Her brother Abshalom \add asked\add* her, “\add Did your half-brother Amnon mess\add* with you? But now, my sister, \add don’t tell anyone since he’s your brother and don’t let it upset you\add*.” \add So\add* Tamar lived \add in a state of desolation\add* in her brother Abshalom’s house.
\p
\v 21 \add When\add* King David heard about all that, \add he got very angry\add*.
\v 22 \add Also,\add* Abshalom said nothing to Amnon (either good or bad) because he hated \add him\add* for humiliating his sister Tamar.
\s1 Abshalom kills Amnon
\s4 Full kingdom
\p
\v 23 Two years passed, then Abshalom’s shearers were in Baal-Hatsor (near Efraim) and Abshalom \add invited\add* all the king’s sons.
\v 24 Abshalom went to the king and \add asked\add* him, “Listen, please, \add the shearers are working for\add* your servant. Please, let the king and his servants come with your servant.”
\p
\v 25 “No, my son,” the king \add replied\add*. “\add There’s too many of us—it would be too expensive\add* for you.” \add Abshalom\add* he urged him, but he wouldn’t go, \add however\add* he did bless him.
\p
\v 26 “But if \add you don’t come\add*,” Abshalom \add insisted\add*, “please let my brother Amnon come with us.”
\p “Why should \em he\em* go with you?” the king \add asked\add*.
\v 27 \add But\add* Abshalom \add insisted, so\add* \add the king\add* \add agreed to\add* send Amnon and \add his\add* other sons.
\v 28 Then Abshalom \add prepared\add* his young men, “Listen now, when Amnon \add gets a bit drunk from\add* the wine and I tell you all, ‘Strike Amnon!’ then you’ll kill him. You all don’t \add need to\add* be afraid \add because\add* I myself am the one commanding you. Be courageous \add warriors\add*.”
\v 29 \add At the right time,\add* Abshalom’s servants did to Amnon what Abshalom commanded \add them\add*. All the rest of the king’s sons \add jumped\add* up and onto their mules and fled \add away\add*.
\p
\v 30 \add While they were still on the way\add*, David heard the news that Abshalom had struck all of his sons and killed them, and none were left alive.
\v 31 The king \add stood\add* up and tore his clothes, then he laid down on the ground. \add Meanwhile\add*, all his servants \add there\add* were tearing their clothes.
\v 32 Then Yonadab (David’s brother Shimeah’s son) \add spoke up\add*, “My master, don’t \add imagine that\add* all those young men, the king’s sons, have been murdered. \add I suspect that\add* only Amnon is dead, because Abshalom \add has been determined to do this ever since\add* his sister Tamar was humiliated.
\v 33 \add So my master, don’t believe the report that all your\add* sons are dead. \add It’s probably\add* only Amnon who’s dead.
\p
\v 34 \add Meanwhile,\add* Abshalom had fled.
\p \add Suddenly\add* the watchman \add turned\add* and saw, wow, many people coming around the hill along the road behind him.
\v 35 “Look,” Yonadab told the king. “The king’s sons are coming! \add It’s just what I said\add*.”
\v 36 He’d \add hardly\add* finished speaking when, wow, the king’s sons came in. Then they all cried loudly, and the king and his servants \add joined them in their wailing\add*.
\p
\v 37 \add But\add* Abshalom \add had\add* fled, and he went to Geshur to stay with King Ammihud’s son, Talmay. \add But\add* \add David\add* mourned for his son every day.\x + \xo 13:37: \xt 2Sam 3:3.\x*
\v 38 \add After\add* Abshalom fled to Geshur, he stayed there for three years.
\v 39 \add By then,\add* King David was \add no longer grieving over Amnon’s death\add* and longed to go to \add see\add* Abshalom.
\c 14
\s1 Abshalom returns to Yerushalem
\s4 Full kingdom
\p
\v 1 \add Now\add* Yoav (Tseruyah’s son) \add realised\add* that the king \add missed\add* Abshalom,
\v 2 \add so\add* he sent for a wise woman from Tekoa and told her, “Now, please put on mourning clothes and don’t \add put on any make-up\add*. \add Act\add* like a woman who has been mourning for the dead for \add several\add* days,
\v 3 and go to the king and \add give him this message\add*.” Then Yoav told her what to say to the king.
\p
\v 4 \add So\add* the Tekoan woman went to the king and \add fell onto her knees with his face down to the ground\add*, saying, “\add Your majesty, help\add* \add me\add*.”
\p
\v 5 “What’s \add the matter\add*?” the king \add asked\add*.
\p “Alas, I’m a widow,” she \add replied\add*. “My husband has died.
\v 6 Your female servant had two sons, and the two of them fought \add each other out\add* in the countryside. There wasn’t anyone there who could \add stop\add* them, and then one \add son\add* struck the other and killed him.
\v 7 \add Now\add* listen, the entire clan has \add turned against\add* your female servant and \add demanded\add*, ‘Give \add us\add* the one who \add killed\add* his brother, and we’ll kill him in exchange for the life of the brother that he killed. Also, \add it would mean that this evil thing couldn’t be passed on\add*.’ \add But that would leave me with no descendants to continue\add* my husband’s name.”
\p
\v 8 “Go \add home\add*,” the king told the woman, “and I’ll \add make a decision about what to do\add*.”
\p
\v 9 \add But\add* the Tekoan woman \add continued\add*, “The \add blame\add*,\f + \fr 14:9 \ft Presumably for not putting the murderer to death.\f* my master the king, \add will be on me and my extended family, but\add* the king and his throne will be innocent.”
\p
\v 10 “Anyone who speaks against you,” said the king, “bring them to me, and then they won’t \add trouble\add* you any more.”
\p
\v 11 “Please,” she \add insisted\add*, “may the king \add ask\add* your God Yahweh to prevent the avenger of blood from increasing the \add tragedy\add*, so my son won’t be destroyed.”
\p “As surely as Yahweh lives,” he \add vowed\add*, “not a hair from your son’s head will fall to the ground.”
\p
\v 12 Then the woman said, “Please, let your female servant \add ask\add* my master the king \add a question\add*.”
\p “Speak,” he \add replied\add*.
\p
\v 13 \add So\add* the woman \add asked\add*, “Why have you \add acted\add* like this against God’s people? When the king says that \add to me\add*, isn’t he convicting himself since he hasn’t \add brought back\add* \em his own\em* \add banished son\add*?
\v 14 \add It’s certain that we’ll\add* \add all\add* die. Water that’s spilt on the ground can’t be gathered together \add again\add* \add but\add* God’s \add not like that\add*. Rather than taking away life, he devises plans so that the one who was banished can be \add gathered back in\add*.
\v 15 \add The reason\add* that I’ve come now to tell this to the king my master, is because the people have frightened me. \add So\add* your servant said \add to herself\add*, ‘I will speak, please, to the king. Perhaps the king will \add honour the request\add* of his female servant.
\v 16 \add Maybe\add* the king will listen in order to save his female servant from the man who’s \add cutting\add* me and my son together \add off\add* from the inheritance given by God.’
\v 17 And your female servant \add thought\add*, ‘Please, let the word of my master the king become \add my assurance\add*, because my master the king is like God’s messenger \add when it comes to\add* understanding good and evil. And may Yahweh your God be with you.’ ”\x + \xo 14:17: \xt 2Sam 19:27.\x*
\p
\v 18 “\add Hang on,\add*” the king told the woman. “\add I want you to answer this question honestly\add*.”
\p “Please, let my master the king speak.” \add she\add* \add responded\add*.
\p
\v 19 “\add Did Yoav perhaps have anything to do\add* with all this?” he \add asked\add*.
\p The woman answered, “By the life of your spirit, my master the king, there’s no \add avoiding anything\add* that my master the king has said. \add Yes,\add* your servant Yoav—he himself commanded me, and he himself \add told\add* your female servant \add what I should say\add*.
\v 20 Your servant Yoav \add set this up to try to remedy the situation\add*. But my master is wise like the wisdom of one of God’s messengers to know everything that’s \add going on here\add* on earth.”
\p
\v 21 Then the king \add summoned\add* Yoav and told him, “\add All right then,\add* I’ll \add sort this out. Now\add* go \add and\add* bring back the young man Abshalom.”
\p
\v 22 Yoav fell \add onto his knees and bowed\add* his face to the ground, and blessed the king, then he said, “Today, your servant knows that I have found favour in your eyes, my master the king, since the king \add is going to do what\add* his servant \add asked\add*.”
\v 23 Then Yoav got up and went to Geshur to get Abshalom and bring him \add back\add* to Yerushalem,
\v 24 \add but\add* the king said, “He can go around to his house, but he’s \add to stay right away from me\add*.” \add So\add* Abshalom \add lived in his own\add* house, \add but wasn’t allowed into the palace\add*.
\s1 Abshalom and David reconcile
\s4 Full kingdom
\p
\v 25 \add Now\add* Abshalom \add was admired as the most handsome man\add* in all Yisrael—from the \add top\add* of his head to the \add bottom\add* of his feet, \add you wouldn’t be able to find a blemish on his skin\add*.
\v 26 He \add had his hair cut once a year when it got too heavy on him, and when the hair was weighed using standard weights, it would be over two kilograms\add*.
\v 27 Abshalom had three sons and a daughter named Tamar—a very attractive woman.
\p
\v 28 Abshalom lived in Yerushalem for two years \add without ever getting to\add* see the king,
\v 29 \add so\add* \add he\add* \add sent a message\add* to Yoav \add about getting an invitation to see\add* the king, but \add Yoav\add* wouldn’t come to him. He sent \add another message\add*, but \add Yoav\add* \add still\add* wouldn’t come,
\v 30 \add so\add* he \add instructed\add* his servants, “Listen, Yoav’s \add piece of land with a barley crop is nearby\add*. Go and set fire to it.” \add So\add* Abshalom’s servants \add burnt\add* \add Yoav’s barley\add*.\f + \fr 14:30 \ft TC: The Septuagint translation adds the following words here: “And Abshalom’s servants burnt them up. Then Yoav’s servants came to him, tearing their garments. They said…”\f*
\p
\v 31 Then Yoav went to Abshalom’s house and \add demanded\add*, “Why did your servants \add destroy my barley crop\add*?”
\p
\v 32 “Listen, I \add tried to contact\add* you,” Abshalom \add replied\add*. “I asked you to come here so that I could send you to the king \add to ask what the point was of bringing me here from Geshur\add* \add if I can’t see him\add*—\add I might as well have stayed back\add* there. \add So\add* now, \add help me to get invited to see\add* the king, and then if \add I’m considered guilty of a crime\add*, then let him kill me.”
\p
\v 33 \add So\add* Yoav went and informed the king, and he called for Abshalom. \add When he entered\add*, he \add knelt and bowed his face\add* to the ground \add in front of\add* the king, and then the king kissed \add him\add*.
\c 15
\s1 Abshalom plans his rebellion
\s4 Full kingdom
\p
\v 1 \add Sometime after all that\add*, Abshalom \add acquired\add* a chariot and horses and \add hired\add* fifty men to run ahead of him.
\v 2 \add He\add* would get up early and stand \add on the side of the road going in and out of the city\add*. \add Every time that someone came into the city to take a dispute to be settled by the king, Abshalom would ask them where they were from, and they’d reply with their city and tribe\add*,
\v 3 then \add he’d\add* say, “Listen, \add No doubt\add* what you’re saying is sensible and right, but the king hasn’t \add appointed anyone to listen to people from your area\add*.”
\v 4 Then Abshalom would \add add\add*, “\add If I was\add* appointed as judge, then every person with a dispute or case could come to me and \add obtain\add* justice.”
\v 5 Whenever anyone approached him to \add bow respectfully\add* to him, he would put out his hand and \add embrace\add* them and kiss them.
\v 6 Abshalom acted \add that way towards every Israeli\add* who came for \add a dispute to be settled by\add* the king, and \add in doing that\add* he stole the \add hearts\add* of the \add Israeli people\add*.
\p
\v 7 Four\f + \fr 15:7 \ft The Hebrew says forty years, but this is interpreted here as a scribal error. (David’s entire reign was only forty years, see 1 Kings 2:11.)\f* years \add later,\add* Abshalom \add begged\add* the king, “Please, \add release me to\add* go and fulfill the vow that I made to Yahweh in Hebron,
\v 8 because when I was living in Geshur (in Aram) \add I promised Yahweh that\add* if he brought me \add back\add* to Yerushalem, then I’d worship him \add in Hebron\add*.”
\p
\v 9 “Go in peace,” the king \add responded, so\add* Abshalom \add left for\add* Hebron.
\v 10 \add From there,\add* \add he\add* sent \add sleeper groups\add* into all \add areas\add* of Yisrael, telling \add them\add*, “When you all hear the trumpet blasts, then \add shout\add*, ‘Abshalom has become king from Hebron!’ ”
\v 11 Abshalom \add had invited\add* two hundred men from Yerushalem to go with him \add to Hebron\add*, but they were innocent and didn’t know what was \add about to happen\add*.
\v 12 Then \add while\add* he was offering sacrifices, Abshalom \add also\add* sent for David’s adviser Ahitofel from Giloh. \add By now\add* the conspiracy was strengthening, and Abshalom \add was becoming popular with more and more\add* people.
\s1 The fleeing of David
\s4 Full kingdom
\p
\v 13 \add Eventually,\add* \add someone went\add* and told David, “The \add loyalty of the Israeli people is turning towards\add* Abshalom.”
\p
\v 14 \add So\add* David told his servants, “\add Pack up quickly and let’s get out of here, or else we won’t be able\add* to escape from Abshalom. \add Be fast in case he’s heading here soon\add* and overtakes us. \add That would be a massacre and the whole city would die from their swords\add*.”
\p
\v 15 “Your servants \add here\add* \add will do everything you tell us\add*,” they \add replied\add* to the king.
\v 16 \add So\add* the king left ten of his slave-wives to \add look after\add* the palace, \add but\add* he left with all his family.
\p
\v 17 \add So\add* the king departed with all his people, and they stopped at the last house.
\v 18 Then all his servants passed beside him to go ahead, along with his bodyguards (the Kerethites and the Felethites) and six hundred Gittites (from Gat).
\v 19 Then the king said to Ittai the Gittite, “\add You don’t have to come\add* with us. You’re a foreigner and an exile from your place, \add so you could\add* go back and stay with the \add new\add* king.
\v 20 \add You haven’t been here long\add*, and we don’t even know where we’re going. \add I certainly need to leave but you can return with your relatives\add*. \add May Yahweh show\add* kindness and faithfulness \add to you all\add*.”
\p
\v 21 “\add As Yahweh lives, and as my master the king lives\add*,” Ittai answered the king, “\add wherever my master the king goes\add*, your servant will certainly be there \add also\add*, whether \add it means life or death\add*.”
\p
\v 22 “\add Okay,\add* go \add ahead then\add*,” David told Ittai. \add So\add* Ittai and all his men and \add their families went with David\add*.
\v 23 \add All the people along the road cried when they saw them walking by\add*. The king and all the others crossed the Kidron riverbed and went up the hill toward the wilderness.
\p
\v 24 \add What a sight!\add* Even Tsadok and all the Levites with him were carrying the box with God’s agreement \add in it\add*, and when they put it down \add again\add*, \add the priest\add* Evyatar caught up \add to them and waited\add* until all the people had finished \add exiting\add* the city.
\v 25 \add But\add* the king told Tsadok, “\add Take the sacred chest back into\add* the city. If Yahweh favours me, then he’ll \add help\add* me return, and he’ll \add let\add* me see it and his \add place of residence\add* \add again\add*.
\v 26 \add But\add* if \add Yahweh\add* says that he isn’t pleased with me, then he’ll do to me \add whatever he thinks best\add*.
\v 27 \add Aren’t you a prophet\add*? Return to the city in peace, along with your son Ahimaats and Evyatar’s son Yonatan.
\v 28 Listen, I’ll wait at the fords in the wilderness until \add I get your message\add*.”
\v 29 \add So\add* Tsadok and Evyatar \add carried the sacred chest\add* back to Yerushalem, then they remained there.
\p
\v 30 \add As\add* David was going up the Mount of Olives, he was walking barefoot with his head covered. He was weeping as were the people with him—they \add too\add* had their heads covered and were weeping.
\v 31 David \add knew\add* that Ahitofel was among the people conspiring with Abshalom, \add so\add* \add he\add* \add prayed\add*, “Please, Yahweh, make Ahitofel \add give foolish advice\add*.”
\p
\v 32 \add When\add* David \add reached the summit\add* (where people \add frequently\add* worship God), Hushay (the Arkite) met him there. He had torn his clothes and put dirt on his head.
\v 33 David told him, “If you \add come\add* with me, you’ll be a burden to me,
\v 34 \add but\add* if you return to the city and tell Abshalom, ‘I’m your servant, \add my\add* king. I was your father’s servant \add in the past, but\add* now I’ll be your servant,’ then you’ll \add be able to oppose\add* Ahitofel’s counsel for me.
\v 35 The priests Tsadok and Evyatar \add are already\add* there, \add so tell\add* \add them\add* \add everything you hear in the palace\add*.
\v 36 \add Also\add* Tsadok’s son Ahimaats and Evyatar’s son Yonatan are there. \add Tell them everything\add* you hear, then send \add them to report it to me\add*.
\p
\v 37 \add So\add* David’s friend Hushay \add slipped back into\add* Yerushalem \add just as\add* Abshalom was entering the city.
\c 16
\s1 Dishonest Tsiva helps David
\s4 Full kingdom
\p
\v 1 David \add hadn’t gone far past the summit when\add*, wow, he was meet by Mefiboshet’s servant Tsiva with a pair of saddled donkeys \add loaded with\add* two hundred bread rolls, one hundred \add cakes\add* of raisins, one hundred \add pieces\add* of fresh fruit, and a \add leather container\add* of wine.\x + \xo 16:1: \xt 2Sam 9:9-10.\x*
\v 2 “\add What’s all that\add*?” the king \add asked\add*.
\p “The donkeys are for the king’s \add family\add* to ride,” Tsiva \add answered\add*, “and the bread and fruits are for the young men to eat, and the wine is for the people to drink who \add feel\add* faint in the wilderness.”
\p
\v 3 “\add So\add* where’s your master’s grandson \add Mefiboshet\add*?” \add asked\add* the king.\x + \xo 16:3: \xt 2Sam 19:25-27.\x*
\p \add Ha\add*, he stayed in Yerushalem because he thought that \add the Israelis might give back control of his grandfather’s kingdom\add*,” Tsiva \add lied\add*.
\p
\v 4 “Well then,” the king told Tsiva, “everything that belonged to Mefiboshet now belongs to you.”
\p “\add I’m honoured\add*,” Tsiva \add responded\add*, “that I’ve found favour in the eyes of my master the king.”
\s1 Shimei curses David
\s4 Full kingdom
\p
\v 5 \add When\add* King David got to Bahurim, wow, a man from Sha’ul’s \add extended family\add* came out. He was Gera’s son Shimei, and he came out and cursed \add David\add*.
\v 6 Then he threw stones at David and all \add his\add* servants, and all the people and \add warriors\add* on \add both sides\add* of \add the king\add*.
\v 7 “Go away, go away, you worthless man of \add much bloodshed\add*!” Shimei \add yelled\add*.
\v 8 “\add Now\add* Yahweh’s returning to you all the blood of Sha’ul’s household. You \add took over as\add* king in his place, \add but\add* Yahweh’s giving the kingdom into the hand of your son Abshalom. Look at you, you’re evil because you’re a man of \add much bloodshed\add*.”
\p
\v 9 The Tseruyah’s son Abishai \add asked\add* the king, “Why should this dead dog curse my master the king? Please, let me cross over and \add lop off\add* his head.”
\p
\v 10 “What \add does it matter\add* to me, or to you \add two\add* sons of Tseruyah?” the king \add replied\add*. “He’s cursing because Yahweh told him to curse \add me\add*, \add so who has any right to ask him why he’s saying it\add*?”
\v 11 Then David told Abishai and all his servants, “Look, my \add own biological son is trying to kill me\add*. \add Now on top of\add* that, this Benjaminite. Leave him and let him curse, because Yahweh \add told him to\add*.
\v 12 Perhaps Yahweh will see my suffering and return good on me, instead of this cursing today.”
\v 13 \add As\add* David and his men \add continued along\add* the road, Shimei walked along the hillside beside him—walking and cursing, and throwing stones and dirt at him.
\v 14 \add Later\add*, the king and all the people with him arrived,\f + \fr 16:14 \ft Probably at the fords mentioned in 15:28.\f* and feeling very tired, they rested.
\s1 The conflicting advice of Hushay and Ahitofel
\s4 Full kingdom
\p
\v 15 \add Meanwhile,\add* Abshalom and \add all his followers\add* arrived in Yerushalem, and Ahitofel was among \add them\add*.
\v 16 \add When\add* David’s friend Hushay (the Arkite) came to Abshalom, he \add greeted\add* \add him\add*, “May the king live. May the king live.”
\p
\v 17 “Is \add that how you show\add* kindness to your friend \add David\add*?” Abshalom \add responded\add*. “Why didn’t you go with \add him\add*?”
\p
\v 18 “No,” Hushay \add replied\add*. “I’ll \add serve whoever\add* Yahweh and these people and all the men of Yisrael have chosen. \add So\add* I’ll stay with \add you\add*.
\v 19 \add Besides that\add*, who should I serve? \add Why shouldn’t I serve my master’s\add* son? Just as I’ve served your father, \add similarly, I’ll serve you\add*.”
\p
\v 20 Then Abshalom \add turned to\add* Ahitofel, “Give us advice. What should we do \add next\add*?”
\p
\v 21 “Go to your father’s slave-wives that he left to guard the house,” Ahitofel \add replied\add*. “\add Lie with them\add* then all Yisrael will hear that you’ve made your father stink, and then \add everyone\add* with you will be \add encouraged\add*.”
\v 22 \add So\add* they \add set up\add* a tent for Abshalom on the \add palace\add* roof and \add he\add* \add had sex\add* with his father’s slave-wives \add where everyone would know what was going on\add*.\x + \xo 16:22: \xt 2Sam 12:11-12.\x*
\p
\v 23 In those days, Ahitofel’s advice was just \add as good as inquiring directly from\add* God, \add so David in the past, and now Abshalom, accepted what he said\add*.
\c 17
\s1 Hushay argues against Ahitofel’s advice
\s4 Full kingdom
\p
\v 1 Then Ahitofel \add asked\add* Abshalom, “Please, let me choose twelve thousand men, then let me \add go\add* and pursue after David tonight.
\v 2 I’ll \add attack\add* him while \add they’re\add* tired and \add lacking energy\add*. \add Once I panic\add* \add them\add*, all the people with him will flee and I’ll be able to strike the king by himself.
\v 3 Then I’ll \add bring\add* all the people \add back\add* to you, like \add a reunion\add*. You’ll \add have\add* the man you’re \add wanting\add*, and all the people will be in peace.”
\v 4 \add That seemed very sensible to\add* Abshalom and all the Israeli elders.
\p
\v 5 \add But\add* Abshalom \add insisted\add*, “Now, call Hushay the Arkite \add as well\add*, and let’s also \add listen to his suggestions\add*.”
\v 6 \add So when\add* Hushay \add arrived\add*, Abshalom \add asked\add* him, “Ahitofel has \add suggested so and so\add*. Should we \add do what he said\add*? If not, \add what would you recommend?\add*”
\p
\v 7 “This time, Ahitofel’s suggestion isn’t \add such\add* good advice,” Hushay \add replied\add*.
\v 8 You yourself know your father and his men—\add and do remember\add* that they’re \add powerful warriors\add*—they’re \add still furious\add* like a bear in the countryside \add that’s been robbed of its cubs\add*. And your father is an \add experienced\add* man of war, and he won’t spend the night \add there\add* with the people.
\v 9 Listen, he’s \add probably\add* \add already hiding in a cavern or some other place\add*. \add Also,\add* if \add some of your men\add* were killed early \add in the fighting\add*, \add then the rumour would go around that Abshalom’s already lost many men\add*.
\v 10 Then \add even your bravest warriors might lose heart\add*, because all Yisrael knows that your father is a \add powerful warrior\add*, and \add also\add* that the men with him are \add very experienced\add*.
\v 11 \add So this is what I suggest\add*: \add Call warriors from\add* all Yisrael—from Dan \add in the far north\add* to Beer-Sheva \add in the far south\add*. They’ll be as numerous as sand \add grains\add* on the beach and you \add personally will be able to lead them into\add* battle.
\v 12 Then we’ll \add be able to find him wherever he is\add*, and \add attack him like dew blankets the entire area\add*, and neither him nor any of the men with him \add will survive\add*, not even one.
\v 13 If he \add escaped into some\add* city, \add we’d all\add* bring ropes to that city and drag \add the stones\add* into the valley until even a pebble couldn’t be found there.”
\p
\v 14 Abshalom and all the \add Israeli elders agreed that Hushay’s advice was better than Ahitofel’s\add*. (Yahweh had \add influenced\add* them to reject Ahitofel’s good advice so \add he\add* could bring disaster onto Abshalom.)
\s1 The warning to David to flee
\s4 Full kingdom
\p
\v 15 Then Hushay told the \add two\add* priests Tsadok and Evyatar what Ahitofel had suggested to Abshalom and the Israeli elders and \add what he’d countered it with\add*.
\v 16 Then \add he told them\add*, “\add Get that message to\add* David quickly. \add Tell him\add* not to \add overnight\add* at the fords in the wilderness, but to cross over otherwise he’ll be killed \add along with everyone else\add* with him.”
\p
\v 17 \add Their sons\add* Yonatan and Ahimaats were waiting at Eyn-Rogel \add where\add* a female servant would come and \add pass the message onto\add* them, because it \add wouldn’t be safe for them\add* to be seen entering the city. Then they themselves would go and inform King David.
\v 18 \add But\add* a young man saw them and informed Abshalom, \add but\add* \add meanwhile\add* the two of them went quickly and got to the house of a man in Bahurim \add where\add* they went down into the well in his courtyard.
\v 19 The woman \add there\add* stretched a covering over the top of the well, and then spread grain over it \add to dry\add*, so \add it wasn’t obvious\add*.
\v 20 \add Some of\add* Abshalom’s servants \add arrived at the house and asked\add* the woman, “Where’s Ahimaats and Yonatan?”
\p “They crossed over the creek,” she \add replied\add*.
\p \add So they continued searching for them, but gave up\add* \add after a while\add* and returned to Yerushalem.
\p
\v 21 \add After they’d gone\add*, \add the two men\add* \add climbed\add* out of the well, and went \add on\add* and informed King David, “\add Pack\add* up and quickly cross over the river, because Ahitofel \add suggested attacking you all immediately\add*.”
\v 22 \add So\add* David and everyone with him \add moved on\add* and crossed the Yordan \add in the night, and by dawn there were all across\add*.
\p
\v 23 \add When\add* Ahitofel saw that his \add advice hadn’t been taken\add*, he saddled his donkey and \add rode\add* to his city. He gave instructions to his \add household\add*, then he hanged himself. \add His body\add* was buried in his father’s tomb.
\p
\v 24 \add Meanwhile,\add* David arrived at Mahanayim, \add but\add* Abshalom and all his men had crossed over the Yordan.
\v 25 As the \add replacement\add* for Yoav as army \add commander\add*, Abshalom had appointed Amasa. (He was Yeter’s son, and his mother was Nahash’s daughter Abigail who was the sister of Yoav’s mother Tseruyah.)
\v 26 Abshalom and \add his men\add* camped in the Gilead \add region\add*.
\p
\v 27 \add While David was in\add* Mahanayim, Shovi (Nahash’s son from Rabbah), Machir (Ammiyel’s son from Lo-Debar), and Barzillai (the Gileadite from Rogelim)
\v 28 \add brought\add* bedding and basins, clay pots, wheat and barley, flour and roasted grain, beans and lentils,
\v 29 honey and yogurt, sheep and cheese for David and the people with him to eat because they \add knew that they’d\add* be hungry and tired and thirsty \add there\add* in the wilderness.
\c 18
\s1 Abshalom’s defeat and death
\s4 Full kingdom
\p
\v 1 David \add divided his warriors into units\add* and appointed commanders of hundreds and of thousands.
\v 2 \add He\add* \add sent them out in three groups under\add* Yoav, Abishai (son of Yoav’s brother Tseruyah) and Ittai (the Gittite), then \add promised that he’d also join them in battle\add*.
\p
\v 3 \add But\add* the people \add complained\add*, “\add No,\add* don’t go out, because if we \add have to\add* flee, they won’t \add be worried about\add* us. \add Even\add* if half of us die, they won’t \add be worried about\add* us, because you \add count more to them than ten thousand of us\add*. \add So\add* it’s better that you \add stay to\add* help us from the city.”
\p
\v 4 “I’ll do whatever seems best to you,” the king \add responded\add*. \add So\add* the king stayed beside the city gate while the \add men\add* went out by their hundreds and thousands.
\v 5 Then he commanded Yoav and Abishai and Ittai, “\add For my sake, don’t harm my son\add* Abshalom.” All the people heard the king \add give this command\add* about Abshalom \add to all the leaders\add*.
\p
\v 6 So \add David’s\add* people went out to the countryside to meet \add the rest of\add* Yisrael. The battle was in the Efraim forest
\v 7 and David’s \add men defeated the rest—twenty thousand men died\add* that day,
\v 8 \add but\add* as the battle had spread over the \add entire area\add*, the forest killed more people that day than the sword.
\p
\v 9 Abshalom happened to meet some of David’s \add men\add*. \add He\add* was riding his mule, and when \add it\add* \add darted\add* under the think branches of a large terebinth \add tree\add*, his head got caught in the branches and he was \add left hanging in the air\add* as the mule \add kept going\add*.
\v 10 \add Someone noticed him\add* and informed Yoav that he’d seen Abshalom hanging in a tree.
\p
\v 11 “\add What!\add*. You saw \add him\add* \add but didn’t strike him down\add*?” Yoav \add challenged\add*. “\add I would have given\add* you ten silver \add coins\add* and a \add leather\add* belt.”
\p
\v 12 “Even if \add you’d placed one thousand silver coins in my hands\add*,” \add he\add* \add replied\add*, “I wouldn’t have \add harmed\add* the king’s son, because \add we heard the king’s command with our own ears about looking out for\add* Abshalom.
\v 13 \add Even if I’d ignored my good sense, the king would have found out about it, then even you wouldn’t have stood up for\add* me.”
\p
\v 14 “\add I’m not going to waste time arguing with you\add*,” Yoav responded, then he took three spears \add and went\add* and thrust them into Abshalom’s \add abdomen\add* while he was \add still alive and dangling from the tree\add*.
\v 15 Then ten young men who carried Yoav’s weapons surrounded Abshalom and \add finished him off\add*.
\p
\v 16 Then Yoav blew the trumpet \add to signal the end of the fighting\add* and the people returned from chasing \add Abshalom’s men\add*.
\v 17 They took Abshalom’s \add body\add* and threw it into a large pit in the forest and covered it with a large pile of stones. \add Meanwhile\add* \add his men\add* fled back to their homes.
\p
\v 18 \add During his lifetime,\add* Abshalom had setup a pillar in the King’s Valley because \add he had no sons to preserve his name\add*. He \add put his name on\add* the pillar and it’s known as ‘Abshalom’s hand’ to this day.
\s1 David learns about Abshalom’s death
\s4 Full kingdom
\p
\v 19 Then Tsadok’s son Ahimaats \add requested\add*, “Please, let me run and let me take the news to the king, because Yahweh has \add rescued\add* him from his enemies.”
\p
\v 20 “\add No, not today\add*,” Yoav \add replied\add*. “\add Some other time I’ll allow you to take some news, but not today\add* because the king’s son is dead.”
\v 21 Then Yoav instructed a Cushite man, “Go and tell the king what you saw.”. The \add man\add* bowed to Yoav and ran \add off\add*.
\p
\v 22 \add But\add* Ahimaats \add begged\add* Yoav again, “\add Regardless of what might happen\add*, please, let me also run myself after the Cushite.”
\p “Why \add would you do that\add*, my \add boy\add*?” Yoav \add asked\add*. “\add There won’t be any reward for\add* \add bad\add* news.”
\p
\v 23 “\add No matter what, I want to\add* run,” \add he replied\add*.
\p “\add Okay then,\add* run,” Yoav told him. \add So\add* Ahimaats \add took a different route through\add* the Yordan valley and \add arrived before\add* the Cushite.
\p
\v 24 \add Now\add* David was sitting between the \add outer and inner\add* gates. \add When\add* the watchman had gone over the gate roof to the wall, he \add looked out\add* and saw, wow, a man was running \add towards them\add* alone.
\v 25 The watchman called \add down\add* and informed the king, and the king said, “If he’s alone, \add he’ll be bringing\add* news.”
\p \add As the runner got closer\add*,
\v 26 the watchman looked and saw another man running. \add He\add* called \add down\add* to the gatekeeper and said, “Look, there’s \add another\add* man running alone.”
\p “He’ll also be bringing news,” said the king.
\p
\v 27 “The \add gait\add* of the first runner is like that of Tsadok’s son Ahimaats,” the watchman said.
\p “He’s a good man and he’ll be bringing good news,” said the king.
\p
\v 28 Then Ahimaats called \add ahead\add* to the king, “Peace!” And he \add knelt down with his face\add* to the ground and said, “Blessed be Yahweh your God, who’s \add stopped\add* the men who \add acted\add* against my master the king.”
\p
\v 29 “Is the young man Abshalom all right?” the king \add asked\add*.
\p “When Yoab sent \add me\add*, your servant,” Ahimaats \add answered\add*, “I \add noticed a big\add* commotion, but I don’t know what \add it was about\add*.”
\p
\v 30 “\add Go and stand over there\add*,” the king \add ordered\add*, so he \add stepped aside\add* and stood \add there\add*.
\p
\v 31 Then, wow, the Cushite \add man\add* arrived and said, “May my master the king receive the good news, because Yahweh has \add rescued\add* you today from all those who rose up against you.”
\p
\v 32 “Is the young man Abshalom all right?” the king asked \add him\add*.
\p The \add man\add* replied, “May the enemies of my master the king and all those who rose up against you for evil, be like that young man \add is\add*.”
\p
\v 33 Then the king \add started\add* trembling, and he went up to the room over the gate, and \add started\add* weeping, saying, “Oh my son Abshalom, my son. Oh my son Abshalom, I wish I’d died instead of you.”
\c 19
\s1 Yoav scolds David
\s4 Full kingdom
\p
\v 1 \add Soon\add* Yoav was told that the king was weeping and mourning over Abshalom’s \add death\add*,
\v 2 and \add so\add* the victory of that day became mourning for all the people, because they’d heard that the king was grieving for his son.
\v 3 The people \add started\add* \add quietly heading back into\add* the city, like people \add would do when they’re ashamed of having to\add* \em flee\em* from a battle.
\v 4 \add But\add* the king covered his face and \add kept\add* crying out loudly, “Oh my son Abshalom. Oh Abshalom, my son, my son.”
\p
\v 5 Then Yoav went to the house \add where\add* the king was and said, “Today you’ve \add made your followers feel ashamed\add*—the ones who saved your life today and the lives of your sons and daughters, and the lives of your wives and your slave-wives.
\v 6 By loving those who hate you and hating those who love you, you’ve \add effectively\add* declared today that your officers and men \add mean\add* nothing to you. \add It seems to us that\add* if Abshalom was still alive today and we were all dead, then it \add would have all been okay to you\add*.
\v 7 \add So\add* get up now and go and speak \add sincerely\add* to your servants, because \add as Yahweh lives\add*, if you don’t then you won’t have a single warrior still with you by the end of the night, and \add that would result in\add* more trouble for you than \add anything else that’s happened\add* to you since you were \add just\add* a lad.”
\v 8 \add So\add* the king got up and \add went and\add* sat at the \add city\add* gate , and \add the news quickly got around\add* and all the people came to \add support\add* the king.
\s1 David returns to Yerushalem
\s4 Full kingdom
\p \add But Abshalom’s warriors had all returned to their homes\add*
\v 9 and \add over time\add*, people \add all across\add* Yisrael began to quarrel and say, “The king rescued us from the \add plans\add* of our enemies \add including\add* the Philistines, but now he’s \add left Israel\add* and fled away from Abshalom.
\v 10 We anointed Abshalom to be over us, but he died in the battle. So why \add aren’t we doing something\add* about returning \add David as\add* king?”
\p
\v 11 \add So\add* King David sent the \add two\add* priests Tsadok and Evyatar to the leaders of Yehudah \add to ask\add*, “Why are you the last \add group\add* to return the king to \add the palace since the king has heard that the rest of Yisrael want it\add*?
\v 12 \add Tell them,\add* ‘You’re all my relatives—my own flesh and blood, \add so\add* why \add would\add* you be the last to \add support me\add* \add again\add*?’ ”
\v 13 And tell Amasa, ‘Aren’t you my \add own\add* flesh and bone? May God \add make me suffer\add* if you don’t become my army commander \add from now on, to replace\add* Yoav.’ ”
\v 14 \add In that way,\add* \add David\add* \add united all the people\add* of Yehudah and they \add notified\add* the king, “\add We all want\add* you and all your servants to return \add here\add*.”
\p
\v 15 \add So\add* the king \add headed back\add* and reached the Yordan River, and \add men from\add* Yehudah went to Gilgal to meet the king and \add help\add* \add him\add* across.
\p
\v 16 Shimei (son of Gera the Benyaminite from Bahurim) hurried down with the Yehudah men to meet King David.\x + \xo 19:16: \xt 2Sam 16:5-13.\x*
\v 17 A thousand Benyamite men \add came\add* with him, as well as Tsiva (formerly Sha’ul’s servant) and fifteen of his sons and twenty of his servants, and they hurried to the Yordan to \add meet\add* the king.
\v 18 They crossed the ford \add to help\add* bring the king’s household \add back\add* \add across\add* and \add anything else the king wanted\add*.
\s1 David’s mercy to Shimei
\s4 Full kingdom
\p Shimei (Gera’s son) fell \add onto his knees in front\add* of the king when he crossed the Yordan
\v 19 and \add begged\add* the king, “May my master not \add consider me guilty\add*, and \add don’t keep thinking about the terrible thing\add* your servant dig on the day that my master the king left Jerusalem—\add don’t brood over it\add*
\v 20 because your servant knows that I myself have sinned, and look, I have come today, first of all the Yosef’s clans to come down to meet my master, the king.”
\p
\v 21 \add But\add* Abishai (Tseruyah’s son) \add answered\add* \add instead\add*, “\add Rather than that\add*, shouldn’t Shimei be killed because he cursed Yahweh’s anointed one?”
\p
\v 22 “You sons of Tseruyah!” David responded. “\add Who asked you\add* \add two\add* \add to accuse others to me today\add*? \add Should today be a time to kill other Israelis\add*? \add Actually, I think it might be\add* \em me\em* who’s Yisrael’s king?”
\v 23 Then the king \add promised\add* Shimei, “You won’t die \add for that\add*.”
\s1 David’s mercy to Mefiboshet
\s4 Full kingdom
\p
\v 24 Then Shaul’s \add grandson\add* Mefiboshet came down to meet the king. He hadn’t \add shaved\add* or \add washed\add* his feet, and he hadn’t washed his clothes \add since the king had left Yerushalem\add*.\x + \xo 19:24: \xt 2Sam 9:1-13; 16:1-4.\x*
\v 25 He came from Yerushalem down to the Yordan to meet the king who \add asked\add* him, “Why didn’t you not \add come\add* with me, Mefiboshet?”
\p
\v 26 “My master the king,” Mefiboshet \add replied\add*, “my servant deceived me. I, your servant, had said to get my donkey saddled so I could ride it and go with \add you\add*, because \add as you know,\add* your servant is lame.
\v 27 Then my servant \add lied to you about me\add*. \add But\add* my master the king is like God’s messenger, so do \add whatever you consider to be appropriate\add*.
\v 28 All my \add grandfather’s household expected that we’d be executed\add*, yet to placed me, your servant, among those who eat at your table, \add so\add* I don’t have the right to \add request anything further from\add* the king.”
\p
\v 29 “\add Say no more\add*,” said the king. “\add That land will be divided for you and Tsiva\add*.”
\p
\v 30 \add Actually\add*, let him take everything,” Mefiboshet responded. “\add since\add* my master the king \add has been able to return safely\add*.”
\s1 David’s kindness to Barzillai
\s4 Full kingdom
\p
\v 31 Barzillai the Gileadite had \add also\add* come down from Rogelim \add to help\add* the king cross the Yordan.\x + \xo 19:31: \xt 2Sam 17:27-29.\x*
\v 32 At eighty, \add he\add* was very old, \add but being very wealthy, he’d provided food and supplies\add* to the king while he’d stayed at Mahanayim,
\v 33 \add so\add* the king told \add him\add*, “You cross over with me, and I’ll provide for you to be with me in Yerushalem.”
\p
\v 34 “How \add much longer am I likely to live\add*?” Barzillai \add pondered\add*. “\add Would it really be worth me moving\add* to Yerushalem with the king?
\v 35 \add Your servant is eighty years old\add*. \add My mind isn’t the same as it was, and I can’t really taste what I\add* eat or drink. \add I can barely hear the sounds\add* of the men and women singing. \add So\add* why would your servant become an extra burden to my master the king?”
\v 36 \add As a token privilege\add*, your servant will cross the Yordan with the king, \add but\add* why should the king reward me with that \add generous\add* reward?
\v 37 Please, let your servant return, and let me die in my city \add near\add* the graves of my \add parents\add*. \add But\add* look, \add here’s\add* your servant Kimham—let him cross over with my master the king, and do \add whatever you consider to be appropriate\add* for him.”
\p
\v 38 “Kimham can cross over with me,” the king said, “and I myself will do for him \add whatever\add* \em you\em* \add consider to be appropriate\add*—everything that you choose concerning me, I’ll do for you.”
\v 39 \add So\add* all the people crossed the Yordan, and then the king crossed \add over\add*. The king kissed Barzillai and blessed him, and then \add Barzillai\add* returned \add home\add*.
\s1 Yehudah and Yisrael disagree
\s4 Full kingdom
\p
\v 40 Then the king crossed over to Gilgal, and Kimham crossed over with him. All the people of Yehudah brought the king over and also \add about\add* half of the people of Yisrael.
\v 41 Then, wow, all the men of Yisrael went to the king and \add demanded\add*, “Why did our \add relatives\add* from Yehudah \add secret\add* you away \add without inviting us\add*? They \add took you and your household\add* over the Yordan, and all \add your\add* men \add as well\add*.”
\p
\v 42 All the men of Yehudah answered the men of Yisrael, “Because the king is \add from our tribe\add*—\add our close relative\add*. \add Why should that make you all angry\add*? \add Do you all think that the king has rewarded us with fancy food or other privileges\add*?”
\p
\v 43 The men of Yisrael answered the men of Yehudah, “\add Our ten tribes\add* \add give us ten shares\add* in the king—more than you. \add So\add* why \add do you look down on us\add*? \add Weren’t we the first to talk about bringing our\add* king back \add to Yerushalem\add*?”
\p \add But\add* \add what the men of Yehudah said\add* was harsher than \add what the ten other tribes said\add*.
\c 20
\s1 Sheva rebels against David
\s4 Full kingdom
\p
\v 1 \add Now there was\add* a good-for-nothing Benyaminite man named Sheva who was Bikri’s son, and he blasted on the trumpet, then said,
\q1 “\add We have no interest\add* in David,
\q1 and no \add claim\add* in Yeshai’s son.
\q1 \add Go home every man from\add* Yisrael.”\x + \xo 20:1: \xt 1Ki 12:16; 2Ch 10:16.\x*
\p
\v 2 \add So\add* all the men of Yisrael \add left\add* David \add and went with\add* Sheva (Bikri’s sons), but the men of Judah \add stayed with\add* their king from the Yordan river and uphill to Yerushalem.
\p
\v 3 \add When\add* David \add got back to his Yerushalem palace\add*, the ten slave-wives that he’d \add left behind\add* to guard the \add palace, \add he\add* \add moved\add* into a separate house\add*. \add That place was\add* guarded and he provided for them, but he didn’t \add sleep with\add* them—\add thus\add* they were locked up until \add they died living as widows\add*.\x + \xo 20:3: \xt 2Sam 16:22.\x*
\p
\v 4 \add One day\add* the king told Amasa \add (his new army commander)\add*, “Summon the men of Yehudah to \add be here in three days, and you be with them\add*.”
\v 5 \add So\add* Amasa went to summon \add them\add*, but he \add took longer than the given time\add*.
\v 6 \add Meanwhile\add* David told Abishai, “Bikri’s son Sheva will do more harm to us now than Abshalom. Take \add some of my warriors\add* and \add chase him down\add*, in case he finds \add some fortified city to hide in and gets away from us\add*.”
\v 7 \add So Yoav’s men and the king’s bodyguards\add* and all the \add best warriors\add* left Yerushalem to \add hunt Sheba down\add*.
\v 8 \add When they were approaching\add* the huge rock at Gibeon, they met Amasa. Yoav was \add dressed for battle with a dagger strapped to his waist under his robe\add*. \add As he stepped forward, he allowed his sword to drop to the ground\add* \add from his hand\add*.
\v 9 Yoav \add greeted\add* Amasa, “\add Is all well with\add* you, my brother?” Then he used his right hand to hold Amasa’s beard to kiss him,
\v 10 \add but\add* Amasa wasn’t aware of the dagger that was in Yoav’s \add other\add* hand. \add Yoav\add* thrust it into \add his\add* stomach and his intestines poured out on the ground. There was no need \add to stab him again\add* and \add Amasa\add* died \add right there\add*.
\p Then Yoav and his brother Abishai \add continued\add* \add their hunt for\add* Bikri’s son Sheva.
\v 11 One of Yoav’s young men stood beside \add Amasa’s body\add* and \add called out\add*, “Whoever favours Yoav and is for David, \add follow\add* Yoav.”
\v 12 \add Amasa’s bloody body\add* was in the middle of the road, and when the \add young\add* man saw that everyone was stopping to look at it, he \add dragged\add* \add it\add* off the road onto the \add grass\add* and threw a \add cloth\add* over it.
\v 13 \add After the body had been removed from the road,\add* all the men \add followed after\add* Yoav to chase Sheva.
\p
\v 14 \add Meanwhile\add* \add Sheva\add* crossed through all the \add tribal regions\add* of Yisrael to Abel-Beyt-Maacah \add where all his relatives gathered together and agreed to back him\add*.
\v 15 \add Yoav’s men\add* arrived and Abel-Beyt-Maacah. They heaped a siege ramp up against the city, and \add also\add* \add pounded\add* the wall to \add try to make it\add* \add collapse\add*.
\v 16 Then a wise woman called out from the city, “Listen, listen, please tell Yoav to come closer \add so I can speak to him\add*.”
\v 17 \add Yoav\add* \add went in closer\add* and \add she\add* asked, “Are you Yoav?”
\p “I am,” he \add replied\add*.
\p “Listen to \add what your servant has to say\add*,” she said.
\p “I’m listening,” he \add answered\add*.
\p
\v 18 Then she told him, “\add Long ago people used to tell others to come here to Abel to get advice, and they’d do that and then be able to settle the matter\add*.
\v 19 I’m a peaceable and faithful \add citizen\add* of Yisrael. You’re \add trying\add* to destroy \add this\add* city and a mother in Yisrael. Why would you \add wipe out our\add* inheritance from Yahweh?”
\p
\v 20 “Far be it, far be it for me that I would \add destroy or wipe it out\add*,” Yoav replied.
\v 21 \add That’s not what we’re here for\add*. \add We’re here\add* for a man from the Efraim hills named Sheva, the son of Bikri. He \add took a stand\add* against the king—against David. \add Just\add* \add hand him over to us, and then we’ll leave your\add* city.”
\p “\add Wait\add*,” the woman told Yoav. “His head will be thrown over the wall to you.”
\v 22 \add So\add* the woman went to all the people \add with\add* her wisdom, and they \add decapitated\add* Sheva, and threw \add his head\add* \add down\add* to Yoav. Then he \add signalled\add* on the trumpet, and \add his men\add* \add left the area and went back to their homes\add*, and Yoav returned to the king at Yerushalem.
\s1 David’s officials
\s4 Full kingdom
\p
\v 23 \add Now\add* Yoav was over the entire Israeli army, and Benayah (Yehoyada’s son) was over the \add kings bodyguards\add*.
\v 24 Adoniram\f + \fr 20:24 \ft ‘Adoram’ is a shortened form of his name.\f* was over the forced labour, and Ahilud’s son Yehoshafat was the secretary and
\v 25 Sheva was the scribe. Tsadok and Evyatar were the priests,
\v 26 and Ira (the Yairite) was David’s priest.
\c 21
\s1 The Gibeonites’ claim on Sha’ul’s descendants
\s4 Full kingdom
\p
\v 1 \add During David’s reign\add*, there was a three-year famine. David inquired from Yahweh who said, “Sha’ul \add and his family have blood on their hands\add*, because he killed the Gibeonites.”
\v 2 (The Gibeonites were not \add native Israelis\add*, but were a remnant of the Amorites. The Israelis had \add promised to protect them\add*, but Sha’ul had attempted to \add eliminate\add* them in his zeal for the people of Yisrael and Yehudah.) \add So\add* the king summoned the Gibeonites and \add asked\add* them,\x + \xo 21:2: \xt Josh 9:3-15.\x*
\v 3 “What can I do for all of you? How can I \add remedy\add* \add what was done in the past\add* so that you all would bless Yahweh’s \add people\add*?”
\p
\v 4 “\add We have no claim\add* to gold or silver from Sha’ul or his household,” the Gibeonites \add replied\add*, “And \add we don’t wish to have anyone\add* in Yisrael put to death.”
\p “Then what are you saying that I can do for you all?” he \add asked\add*.
\p
\v 5 “That man who \add crushed\add* us,” they \add replied\add*, “and who intended \add that we be annihilated from within\add* Yisrael’s borders,
\v 6 give us seven \add of his descendants\add* and we’ll hang them before Yahweh in Gibeah \add where Yahweh’s chosen king Sha’ul lived\add*.
\p “\add Okay\add*, I’ll give them to you,” the king \add responded\add*.
\p
\v 7 \add However\add*, the king \add spared\add* Yonatan’s son (and Sha’ul’s grandson) Mefiboshet because of the promises that he and Yonatan \add had made to each other before\add* Yahweh.\x + \xo 21:7: \xt 1Sam 20:15-17; 2Sam 9:1-7.\x*
\v 8 \add Instead\add* \add he\add* took two of the sons (Armoni and Mefiboshet) of Ritsfah (Ayyah’s daughter \add and one of Sha’ul’s slave-wives\add*), as well as five sons of Sha’ul’s daughter Michal, that she’d bore to Adriel (the son of Barzillai, the Meholatite).\x + \xo 21:8: \xt 1Sam 18:19.\x*
\v 9 He \add handed them over to\add* the Gibeonites, and they hung them on a hill \add before\add* Yahweh, and the seven of them \add died\add* together. \add This happened at\add* the beginning of the barley harvest.
\p
\v 10 Then Ayyah’s daughter Ritsfah took sackcloth and she spread it on the rock \add where the corpses were\add*. She \add kept the birds away during the\add* day and the animals at night—\add staying there\add* from the beginning of the harvest until \add the beginning of the rainy season\add*.
\p
\v 11 \add David was told\add* what Ritsfah had done,
\v 12 and \add he\add* went and got the bones of Sha’ul and his son Yonatan from the \add leaders\add* of Yabesh-Gilead, who had stolen them from the square of Beyt-Shan where the Philistines had hung them there on the day the Philistines had \add defeated\add* Sha’ul at Gilboa.\x + \xo 21:12: \xt 1Sam 31:8-13.\x*
\v 13 \add David\add* took Sha’ul and Yonatan’s bones along with the bones of the \add seven\add* \add men\add* who’d been hung,
\v 14 and \add his men\add* buried \add them\add* in the tomb of Sha’ul’s father Kish in Zela (in the Benyamite region), doing everything that the king had commanded. After that, God \add answered their prayers\add* for the \add country\add*.
\s1 Battles against Philistine giants
\s4 Full kingdom
\r (1 Chr. 20:4-8)
\p
\v 15 The Philistines started attacking Yisrael again, and David and his men went down \add towards the coast\add* and fought \add back\add*, but David \add became exhausted\add*.
\v 16 \add The Philistines had a champion\add* named Yishbi-Benov who was a descendant of giants. He wore new \add armour\add* and his bronze spear \add weighed over three kilograms\add*. He \add intended\add* to kill David
\v 17 \add but\add* Tseruyah’s son Abishai helped \add David\add*, and he struck the Philistine and killed him. Then, David’s men \add made a decision\add*, saying, “You won’t go out to battle with us anymore \add because we don’t want\add* Yisrael’s lamp to be extinguished.”\x + \xo 21:17: \xt 1Ki 11:36; Psa 132:17.\x*
\p
\v 18 \add Some time\add* after that, there \add was another battle\add* with the Philistines at Gov, and Sibbecai (the Hushathite) \add killed\add* Saph who was \add another descendant\add* of the giants.
\p
\v 19 Then in \add another\add* battle with the Philistines at Gov, Elhanan (son of Yaare-Oregim, from Beyt-Lehem) \add killed\add* Goliath the Gittite \add even though\add* his spear \add handle\add* was like a weaver’s beam.
\p
\v 20 In a \add different\add* battle in Gat, there was a \add fierce man\add* there with \add six fingers on each hand and six toes on each foot\add* who was also a descendant of the giants,
\v 21 \add but when\add* he taunted Yisrael, Yonatan (son of David’s brother Shimeah) \add killed\add* him.
\v 22 Those four \add men\add* were descendants of the giants in Gat, \add but\add* they were \add killed\add* by David and his \add men\add*.
\c 22
\s1 David’s song of praise
\s4 Full kingdom
\r (Psa. 18)
\p
\v 1 Then after Yahweh had rescued David from Sha’ul and all his enemies, David \add sang this song\add* for Yahweh,
\q1
\v 2 “Yahweh is my rock and my fortress
\q1 and \add the one who rescues me\add*, \add yes,\add* even me.
\q1
\v 3 God of my rock—I \add find safety\add* in him,
\q1 my shield and \add my powerful saviour\add*,
\q1 my \add high fort\add* and my refuge,
\q1 my saviour—you save me from violence.
\q1
\v 4 I call out to Yahweh who \add deserves\add* to be praised.
\q1 I was kept safe from my enemies.
\b
\q1
\v 5 Death \add was enveloping me like a wave\add*.
\q1 Torrents of worthlessness were overwhelming me.
\q1
\v 6 Sheol’s ropes \add tightened around me\add*.
\q1 Deadly traps confronted me.
\q1
\v 7 In my distress I called to Yahweh,
\q1 and to my God I called out.
\q1 He listened to my voice from his temple,
\q1 and \add he heard\add* my cry for help.
\b
\q1
\v 8 The earth reeled and it shook.
\q1 The foundations of the heavens trembled,
\q2 and they shook because \add because he became angry\add*.
\q1
\v 9 Smoke went up from his nose,
\q1 and burning coals and fire from his mouth.
\q1
\v 10 He stretched out the heavens,
\q1 then he came down and \add it was dark below him\add*.
\q1
\v 11 He rode on a \add winged creature\add*, and he flew.
\q1 \add Yes,\add* he was seen on the wings of the wind.
\q1
\v 12 He placed darkness all around him as a covering—
\q1 a \add collection\add* of dark clouds \add holding water in them\add*.
\q1
\v 13 From the brightness in front of him,
\q2 coals of fire burnt.
\b
\q1
\v 14 Yahweh thundered from the sky.
\q1 The most high \add God\add* \add made his voice known\add*.
\q1
\v 15 He sent out arrows, and he scattered them.
\q1 \add He sent out\add* lightning, and he confused them.
\q1
\v 16 The channels of the sea \add became visible\add*.
\q1 The foundations of the world were uncovered
\q2 at Yahweh’s rebuke,
\q2 from the \add blast from his nostrils\add*.
\q1
\v 17 He \add reached down from above and picked me up\add*.
\q1 He \add pulled me up out of the surging waters\add*.
\q1
\v 18 He rescued me from my powerful enemy—
\q2 from the people who hated me—
\q1 because they were stronger than me.
\q1
\v 19 They \add confronted\add* me \add when I was experiencing difficulties\add*,
\q2 but Yahweh supported me.
\q1
\v 20 He brought me out into a wide area.
\q1 He rescued me because he was pleased with me.
\b
\q1
\v 21 Yahweh has rewarded me \add because of my obedience\add*.
\q1 He’s repaid me because \add my hands were clean\add*,
\q1
\v 22 because I’ve followed Yahweh’s paths,
\q1 and I haven’t acted wickedly \add by turning\add* away from my God.
\q1
\v 23 \add I’m aware of\add* all his regulations,
\q1 and I haven’t turned away from his decrees.
\q1
\v 24 \add I’ve done nothing that he can accuse me of\add*,
\q1 and I’ve \add stopped myself when I wanted to disobey\add*.
\q1
\v 25 Yahweh \add rewarded me for my obedience\add*,
\q1 \add because he saw my innocence\add*.
\b
\q1
\v 26 With a faithful person, you show yourself faithful.
\q1 with a blameless \add warrior\add*, you prove yourself blameless.
\q1
\v 27 With \add someone\add* who purifies themself, you show yourself pure,
\q1 ^\add but\add* you show yourself deceptive to a crooked \add person\add*.
\q1
\v 28 You save afflicted people,
\q1 ^but \add you dislike\add* the proud—you bring \add them\add* down.
\b
\q1
\v 29 For you are my lamp, Yahweh,
\q1 and \add you\add* lighten my darkness.
\q1
\v 30 For by you, I can charge against a troop of warriors.
\q1 With my God’s \add help\add* I can leap over a \add city\add* wall.
\b
\q1
\v 31 God’s path is perfect.
\q1 Yahweh’s message is \add tried and tested\add*.
\q1 →He \add keeps everyone safe who requests his protection\add*.
\q1
\v 32 Who could be God other than Yahweh?
\q1 And who is a rock apart from our God?
\q1
\v 33 This God is my strong fortress,
\q1 and he \add keeps my pathways cleared\add*.
\q1
\v 34 The one who makes my feet \add nimble\add* like a deer,
\q1 and places me securely up on the heights.\x + \xo 22:34: \xt Hab 3:19.\x*
\q1
\v 35 The one who trains \add me how to win in battle\add*,
\q1 and \add strengthens\add* my arms to pull back a \add powerful\add* bow.
\b
\q1
\v 36 You \add saved me\add* \add from death\add* \add like a\add* shield,
\q1 and \add you helped me become well-known by\add* answering \add my prayers\add*.
\q1
\v 37 You \add helped me make large strides\add*,
\q1 and \add stopped\add* my feet from slipping.
\q1
\v 38 Let me chase down my enemies and destroy them.
\q1 Then I won’t return until they’re \add all defeated\add*.
\q1
\v 39 I will \add attack\add* them and smash them.
\q1 They won’t stand \add again\add*—they’ll fall under my feet.
\q1
\v 40 You \add give me extra strength\add* for the war.
\q1 You make the people who \add rebelled against\add* me \add submit\add*.
\q1
\v 41 \add You make my enemies flee away from me\add*.
\q1 \add You help me\add* destroy the people who hate me.
\q1
\v 42 They look, but there’s \add no one to rescue them\add*.
\q1 \add They call out\add* to you, Yahweh, but you don’t answer them.
\q1
\v 43 I crush them \add as finely\add* as the dust on the ground.
\q1 I trample them like the mud on the streets and flatten them.
\b
\q1
\v 44 You rescue me from the arguments of my people.
\q1 You \add help me remain\add* as the head of nations.
\q1 People serve me \add even if I don’t even know them\add*.
\q1
\v 45 Foreigners \add are afraid of\add* me.
\q1 \add When they hear me\add*, they obey me.
\q1
\v 46 \add They\add* lose heart,
\q1 and come \add out\add* of their fortresses trembling.
\b
\q1
\v 47 Yahweh is alive—may my \add secure\add* rock be blessed.
\q1 May the God of the rock of my salvation be praised.
\q1
\v 48 He’s the God who avenges me,
\q1 and the one who makes the people who \add rebelled against\add* me \add submit\add*.
\q1
\v 49 He’s the one who \add helps me escape\add* from my enemies.
\q1 You hold me up \add away\add* from the ones who rise up against me.
\q1 You rescue me from violent \add men\add*.
\b
\q1
\v 50 Therefore I praise you, Yahweh, among the nations,
\q1 and I sing praises \add about who you are\add*.\x + \xo 22:50: \xt Rom 15:9.\x*
\q1
\v 51 \add The one who\add* \add helps his king to save\add* \add the people\add*,
\q1 and the one who shows loyalty to the one he chose—
\q1 to David and to his \add descendants\add* forever.”
\c 23
\s1 David’s ending speech
\s4 Full kingdom
\p
\v 1 These are David’s final words:
\q1 “The message from Yeshai’s son David—
\q1 a message from the man who \add rose through the ranks\add*—
\q2 who was selected by Yakob’s God—
\q1 \add singer of\add* Yisrael’s pleasant songs.
\q1
\v 2 Yahweh’s spirit spoke through me.
\q1 His message \add came out of my mouth\add*.
\q1
\v 3 Yisrael’s God spoke to me.
\q1 The rock of Yisrael told \add me\add*.
\q1 The one who rules \add people with justice\add*,
\q1 →rules out of his respect for God.
\q1
\v 4 He’s like the rising sun bringing the morning light—
\q2 a cloudless morning.
