\s1 David’s top warriors
\s4 Full kingdom
\r (1 Chr. 11:10-41)
\p
\v 8 These are the names of David’s \add top\add* warriors:
\p \bd Yoshev-Bashshevet\bd* the Tahkemonite was the head of ‘The Three’. One time he attacked and killed eight hundred men with his spear.
\p
\v 9 Next after him was \bd Eleazar\bd*, the son of Ahohi’s son Dodo. \add Once he was\add* among the three powerful warriors with David when they taunted the Philistines who were gathered there for battle. The Israeli warriors \add retreated back up\add* their hill,
\v 10 \add but\add* \add Eleazar\add* \add moved forward and attacked the Philistines until his arm became weak, and his hand cramped around\add* his sword. Yahweh \add achieved\add* a great victory that day, and the \add other warriors\add* only returned afterwards to plunder \add the dead\add*.
\p
\v 11 Then there was Agge’s son \bd Shamma\bd*, the Hararite. The Philistines had assembled in formation where there happened to be a field full of lentils. The \add Israelis\add* fled from the Philistines
\v 12 \add but\add* \add Shamma\add* remained there in the middle of the field and killed \add many\add* Philistines. \add So the field was saved\add*, and Yahweh \add achieved\add* a great victory.
\p
\v 13 \add Once\add* as it was approaching harvest time, three of ‘The Thirty’ went to where David \add had been staying\add* at Adullam’s cave. There was a Philistine unit camped in the Refaim valley.
\v 14 At the time, David was in the fortress, and there was \add another\add* Philistine unit in Beyt-Lehem.
\v 15 David \add was thirsty\add* \add one day\add* and \add asked\add*, “Who’ll \add get me a drink of water\add* from the Beyt-Lehem well by the gate?”
\v 16 \add So\add* the three powerful warriors \add broke through\add* the Philistine camp and got water from the Beyt-Lehem well near the gate. They carried it back to David, but he wouldn’t drink it—pouring it out instead \add as an offering\add* to Yahweh,
\v 17 saying, “Far be it for me, Yahweh, \add to drink\add* this—the blood of the men who \add risked\add* their lives.” \add So\add* he wasn’t willing to drink it.
\p Those \add were some of the\add* things done by ‘The Three’ powerful warriors.
\p
\v 18 Yoav’s brother \bd Abishai\bd* (Tseruyah’s sons) was the head over ‘The Three’. \add Once\add* he was \add used\add* his spear to kill three hundred \add fighters\add*, \add so he was more famous\add* than ‘The Three’.
\v 19 He was more honoured than ‘The Three’ and became their leader \add even though he wasn’t one of\add* ‘The Three’.
\p
\v 20 Yehoyada’s son \bd Benayah\bd* from Kavtsael was a man of military prowess with many deeds \add to his name\add*. \add Once\add* he killed ‘The Two’ from Moab, and \add another time\add* he went down in a pit on a snowy day and killed the lion in the pit.
\v 21 He \add also\add* killed an impressive Egyptian warrior with a spear, even though Benayah \add only held\add* a staff. \add First\add* he snatched the spear from the Egyptian’s hand, then he killed him with his \add own\add* spear.
\v 22 Those \add were some of the\add* things that Benayah did. He \add became famous\add* alongside ‘The Three’.
\v 23 (He was more honoured than ‘The Thirty’ but never entered ‘The Three’.) David appointed him over his bodyguard.
\p
