\c 24
\s1 David takes a census
\s4 Full kingdom
\r (1 Chr. 21:1-27)
\p
\v 1 Then Yahweh \add was angry\add* against Yisrael again and he incited David \add to cause problems for\add* them by saying, “Go \add and\add* \add order a census of\add* Yisrael and Yehudah.”
\v 2 \add So\add* the king told Yoav, the commander of his army, who was with him \add at the time\add*, “\add Travel throughout\add* all the \add regions of\add* the Israeli tribes, from Dan \add (in the far north)\add* down to Beer-Sheva \add (in the far south)\add*, and count the people so that I’ll know the number of \add fighting men\add*.”
\p
\v 3 “May your God Yahweh multiply the people a hundred times \add over\add*,” Yoav responded, “add may my master the king \add see that happen, but\add* why would my master the king \add want to do that\add*?”
\v 4 \add However,\add* the king \add insisted, so even though\add* Yoav and the army commanders \add disagreed\add*, \add at the king’s command\add* \add they\add* \add set off to count\add* the Israeli people.
\p
\v 5 They crossed the Yordan \add river\add* and camped in Aroer, south of the city in the middle of the Gad valley, then \add proceeded\add* to Yazer.
\v 6 Then they went \add north\add* to Gilead and the land of Tahtim-Hodshi, \add before\add* coming to Dan-Yaan and around to Tsidon.
\v 7 Then they came to the Tsor \add (Tyre)\add* fortress and all the cities of the Hivites and the Canaanites \add before going\add* \add east\add* to Beersheva in the Negev \add wilderness\add* (part of Yehudah).
\v 8 \add So they travelled throughout the land for\add* nine months and twenty days \add before returning\add* to Yerushalem.
\v 9 Then Yoav \add reported the census results\add* to the king: 800,000 fighting swordsmen in Yisrael, and 500,000 in Yehudah.
\p
\v 10 \add However, David had a guilty conscience\add* after he’d had the people counted and he told Yahweh, “I’ve \add disobeyed you badly, but\add* now, Yahweh, please \add take away\add* the iniquity of your servant because I’ve been very foolish.”
\p
\v 11 \add When\add* David got up in the morning, Yahweh \add gave\add* the prophet Gad \add this\add* message
\v 12 to take to David, “I, Yahweh, am \add offering you three choices\add*. \add You decide which one I should carry out against\add* you.”
\v 13 Then Gad \add asked\add* \add him\add*, “\add Do you want\add* seven years of famine in your country, or three months of fleeing from your enemies, or three days of plague in your country? \add Consider those and let me know which option to pass back\add* to the one who sent me.”
\p
\v 14 David \add answered\add* Gad, “\add This is very distressing\add*, \add but\add* please \add let Yahweh be the one to punish me because he’s very merciful—don’t let other men be the ones\add*.”
\p
\v 15 \add So\add* Yahweh \add sent\add* a plague to Yisrael from the morning and until the time \add he’d decided\add*. Seventy thousand people died from Dan \add in the north\add* \add down\add* to Beer-Sheva \add in the south\add*.
\v 16 \add When\add* \add Yahweh’s\add* messenger stretched out his hand to destroy Yerushalem \add with the plague\add*, Yahweh relented concerning the disaster and told the messenger who was \add destroying\add* many people, “Now lower your hand.” \add When he said that,\add* \add his\add* messenger was near the threshing floor of Aravnah the Yebusite.
\p
\v 17 David \add had complained\add* to Yahweh when he saw the messenger \add afflicting\add* the people, \add saying\add*, “Listen, \add it’s me alone who\add* sinned, and I myself \add who disobeyed you\add*. \add But\add* these \add innocent\add* \add people\add*—what have they done? Please, \add just punish only me and my relatives\add*.”
\s2 David builds an altar
\p
\v 18 Gad came to David that day, and \add instructed\add* him, “Go to the Yebusite Aravnah’s threshing floor \add and\add* \add build\add* an altar to Yahweh \add there\add*.”
\v 19 \add So\add* David went \add there just as Yahweh had instructed him through Gad’s message\add*.
\v 20 \add When\add* Aravnah looked \add out\add* and saw the king and his servants \add approaching\add*, \add he\add* went out and \add fell to his knees in front of the king and bowed his face\add* to the ground.
\v 21 “Why would my master the king come to his servant?” Aravnah asked.
\p “\add I want to buy your\add* threshing floor to build an altar for Yahweh,” David \add answered\add*. “\add So\add* that the plague \add afflicting\add* the people \add can be stopped\add*.”
\p
\v 22 “May my master the king take \add it\add*,” Aravnah responded. “\add Use it in whatever way you think best\add*. See, \add you can use\add* the oxen for the burnt offering, and the threshing instruments and the oxen’s equipment for firewood.
\v 23 \add I\add* give \add it all\add* to \add you\add*, the king. May your God Yahweh accept your \add offering\add*.”
\p
\v 24 “No,” the king \add answered\add*. “I’ll definitely \add buy\add* it from you. I couldn’t \add offer something to\add* my God Yahweh \add that cost me\add* nothing.”
\v 25 \add So\add* David built an altar there to Yahweh, and he \add instructed for\add* burnt offerings and peace offerings to \add be made\add*. Then Yahweh \add accepted prayers for the country\add* and the plague against Yisrael was \add stopped\add*.
